# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: beam-engine
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:beam-engine/a38-m] The **A38(M)**, commonly known as the **Aston Expressway**, is a motorway in Birmingham, England.
[src:beam-engine/a38-m] It is 2 miles (3.2 km) long and was opened on 24 May 1972.
[src:beam-engine/a38-m] It connects the M6 motorway to Aston and Central Birmingham and forms part of the much longer A38 route.
[src:beam-engine/a38-m] It is extremely unusual as it is the only single carriageway motorway in the United Kingdom and consists of seven lanes with no central reservation, and operates a tidal flow system in an attempt to minimise congestion.
[src:beam-engine/a38-m] Due to the nature of the road, the speed limit is reduced to 50 mph (80 km/h) for most of its length with a very short length of 30 mph (48 km/h).
[src:beam-engine/a38-m] When construction work of the motorway began in the late 1960s, many late 19th-century and early 20th-century houses in the Aston area had to be demolished to make way for the new route.
[src:beam-engine/a38-m] The A38(M) runs from the A5127 through Gravelly Hill Interchange where the A38 joins and then shortly after traffic from the M6 motorway also joins.
[src:beam-engine/a38-m] The road is on a viaduct as it passes through Aston; this section cuts through the grounds of Aston Hall.
[src:beam-engine/a38-m] The road passes through its first junction after 1 mile (1.6 km).
[src:beam-engine/a38-m] It enters a cutting before reaching the second junction, where the tidal flow ends as does the motorway.
[src:beam-engine/a38-m] The motorway is curved in Aston to avoid an Ansells brewery.
[src:beam-engine/a38-m] The motorway was also crossed by a vinegar pipeline, carrying the condiment from one part of the since-demolished HP Sauce factory to the other.
[src:beam-engine/a38-m] The traffic island at Dartmouth Circus was built where Aston Road met with Dartmouth Street, Bracebridge Street and Allesley Street. where the White Hart public house had been sited.
[src:beam-engine/a38-m] The engine was built in 1817 and used in Netherton at the ironworks of M W Grazebrook.
[src:beam-engine/a38-m] The Expressway was the first road in the United Kingdom to introduce tidal flow to allow better management of traffic.
[src:beam-engine/a38-m] Lane use is controlled by means of electronic overhead signs, with one lane always closed to create a buffer between the two directions of travel – there is no central reservation.
[src:beam-engine/a38-m] During the morning rush, four of the seven lanes are allocated to traffic heading into the city and two to traffic heading out of it.
[src:beam-engine/a38-m] In the evening, this pattern is reversed.
[src:beam-engine/a38-m] At all other times, the road runs with three lanes in each direction.
[src:beam-engine/a38-m] Motorcycles are banned from the red-surfaced central lane, which contains a drainage channel, regardless of how it is being used.
[src:beam-engine/a38-m] This follows a fatal accident which occurred when one of the drainage covers came loose.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-pumping-station] The **Abbey Pumping Station** is a museum of science and technology in Leicester, England, on Corporation Road, next to the National Space Centre.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-pumping-station] With four working steam-powered beam engines from its time as a sewage pumping station, it also houses exhibits for transport, public health, light and optics, toys and civil engineering.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-pumping-station] The building was constructed in 1891 by Leicester Corporation on the north side of Leicester, alongside the River Soar, as a pumping station used to pump the town's sewage to the sewage farm at Beaumont Leys.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-pumping-station] The grand Victorian building, designed by Stockdale Harrison (Leicester architect) in 1890, houses four Woolf compound beam engines built by Gimson and Company of Leicester.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-pumping-station] The first attempt to respond to the population's sewage disposal was in 1850 when piped water made water closets possible, and Thomas Wicksteed designed and built sewers leading to a sedimentation and deodorisation treatment works on the northern, downstream, edge of the town.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-pumping-station] Limited capacity and high costs meant that a Pail closet system continued to be used for poorer neighbourhoods.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-pumping-station] As the town expanded so did the problems of pollution in the River Soar from the treatment works.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-pumping-station] Disposal of the night soil from the pail closets, via railway wagons and canal barges, caused complaints of smell and pollution.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-pumping-station] A new solution was needed and the answer was to pump everything to a sewage farm on higher ground at Beaumont Leys.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-pumping-station] The Abbey Pumping Station replaced a smaller facility at Knighton.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-pumping-station] The pumping station was fed by two main trunk sewers, one from the East of the city that ran under Bruin Street and then under the Grand Union Canal, and another that ran along the route of Abbey Lane and then across fields.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-pumping-station] By 1912, the 2,000-acre sewage farm and pumping capacity of up to 20 million gallons a day was insufficient to meet the needs of the growing city, with 130 miles of new sewers built since the station opened, and extensions were agreed.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-pumping-station] In 1939 a ram pump was installed, reportedly the largest of its kind in Europe at the time.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-pumping-station] The station continued pumping Leicester's sewage until 1964, when electric pumps took over, and within a few years the Wanlip Sewage Treatment plant took over and the pumping station was no longer needed.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-pumping-station] In 1972 the building re-opened as a museum of science and technology, run by Leicestershire Museums.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-pumping-station] The huge beam engines were retained intact, and were gradually restored to full working order.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-pumping-station] It is one of several historic pumping stations which have been preserved.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-pumping-station] Leicester City Council became a unitary authority in 1997 and the Abbey Pumping Station is one of the museums that is within their jurisdiction.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-pumping-station] The steam engines (see below) which drive the sewage pumps can be seen.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-pumping-station] In addition, there is combination of informative educational displays (mainly about water and sewage), an old-fashioned film theatre, and collections of artifacts and pictures ranging from domestic appliances to trams.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-pumping-station] An eclectic collection of larger items of industrial archeology is in the grounds.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-pumping-station] This includes a narrow-gauge railway and some transport items.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-pumping-station] The four steam engines were built in Leicester by Gimson and Company and today are rare examples of Woolf compound rotative beam engines.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-pumping-station] At the time these engines were built they were considered an old-fashioned but very well-established design.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-pumping-station] The cast-iron flywheels are 21 feet (6.4 m) diameter and the beams are of plain steel plate construction and 28 feet (8.5 m) long.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-pumping-station] The engines are of 200 indicated horsepower each.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-pumping-station] These engines are rated at 200 hp, at 12–19 rpm, of which they pumped 208,000 imperial gallons of sewage an hour (263 L/s).
[src:beam-engine/abbey-pumping-station] All four engines have been restored to working condition by a team of volunteers: the Leicester Museums Technology Association.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-pumping-station] It is the only engine house in the world where you can see four working examples of the same beam engine in one building.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-pumping-station] Current projects in the engine house are the ongoing maintenance of the latest restored engine, No.1 (restored over a period of 4 years by the volunteers).
[src:beam-engine/abbey-pumping-station] The Pumping Station is normally open Daily from 11am - 4:30pm.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-pumping-station] Engines can be seen in steam at various steam days along with other steam and early internal combustion exhibits.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-pumping-station] The Museum has a narrow-gauge railway which is normally operated by *Leonard*, an 0-4-0ST 2 ft (610 mm) narrow-gauge locomotive built by W.G.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-pumping-station] Bagnall, Stafford as works number 2087 in 1918, but four diesel locomotives – two Simplex, one Lister and one Ruston – are also available if needed.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-pumping-station] There is also a collection of vintage road vehicles which are operated on selected days.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-pumping-station] Exhibits include several fire engines, buses (see below), an 1894 Aveling and Porter steam roller, several diesel rollers, a Bedford fish and chips van, an ex Leicester Corporation Tramways tower wagon and an Austin K2 brewery dray lorry with ales.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-pumping-station] The Ghost of an Engineer who died after falling from a great height whilst working at the Pumping Station in 1890 is said to Haunt the Building.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] The area takes its name from Lesnes Abbey Woods, located to the east, which once belonged to the monks of Lesnes Abbey.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] The Abbey of St Mary and St Thomas the Martyr at Lesnes (or Lesnes Abbey) was founded in 1178 by Richard de Luci, Chief Justiciar of England.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] The Abbot of Lesnes Abbey was an important local landlord, and took a leading part in draining the marshland.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] However, this and the cost of maintaining river embankments was one of the reasons given for the Abbey's chronic financial difficulties.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] It never became a large community, and was closed by Cardinal Wolsey in 1525, under a licence to suppress monasteries of fewer than seven inmates.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] It was one of the first monasteries to be closed after the Dissolution of the Monasteries in 1524, and the monastic buildings were all pulled down, except for the Abbot's Lodging.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] Henry Cooke acquired the site in 1541 and it eventually passed to Sir John Hippersley who salvaged building materials, before selling the property to Thomas Hawes of London in 1632.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] It was then bequeathed to Christ's Hospital in 1633.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] Abbey Wood railway station was opened in 1849, immediately to the north of the area now known as "The Village", built where Knee Hill became Harrow Manorway.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] Contemporary maps show Knee Hill as a minor track compared with a more major pathway through the centre of the existing woods.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] The Village consisted of a dozen or so cottages, and two pubs, the Abbey Arms (next to the railway station) and the Harrow Inn (demolished in 2009).
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] Abbey Wood was suggested as a site for a cemetery serving east London at a time of burial crisis in the capital.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] The Treasury was sceptical that Chadwick's scheme would ever be financially viable, and it was widely unpopular.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] Although the Metropolitan Interments Act 1850 (13 & 14 Vict. c.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] 52) authorised the scheme, it was abandoned in 1852.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] The Royal Arsenal Co-operative Society (RACS) owned two farms on the hillside to the south of The Village; between 1900 and 1930, the RACS built the Bostall Estate, designed by architect Frank Bethell.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] The housing is largely traditional of the "two-up, two-down" design, in distinctive yellow London brick, with gardens to the front and rear.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] A description of the innovative construction processes used to construct the houses 'in a thoroughly substantial manor' is detailed here, which included digging a chalk mine locally for plaster.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] This mine was subsequently used as a bomb shelter in World War I.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] Between 1955 and 1959, the London County Council built the Abbey Estate starting with one road south of the railway and later extending on the northern side on former Royal Arsenal marshland.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] Predominantly conventional brick houses with gardens, at first there were no shops or pubs, later equipped with a few shops and pubs together with schools and open spaces were added.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] Transport was non-existent at first until one bus, the route 180 was added after the building of Eynsham bridge.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] The estate was first used to rehouse people from Dockhead and Peckham then London's East End.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] In the mid-1960s, the Greater London Council (GLC) began building the first phase of Thamesmead on more ex-Royal Arsenal land, north-east of Abbey Wood station.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] When it was initially developed, Thamesmead was envisioned as a revolutionary 'city within a city' of 60,000 people, providing much needed affordable homes with suitable amenities, surrounded by a lake and landscaped parkland exploiting its riverside position.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] It was designed in keeping with the emerging 'Brutalist' aesthetic.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] Despite being the culmination of the GLC's housing works, ultimately only stages 1 and 2 were completed, and the master plan was only partially realised.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] Abbey Wood station is the south east terminus for the Elizabeth line, which opened in 2022, with direct travel times of 11 minutes to Canary Wharf and 25 minutes to Bond Street.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] The distinctive new station has transformed the area, resolving complex urban design issues and delivering a seamless multi modal interchange.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] A decade after work began on the line, Abbey Wood has seen the strongest price growth across London, at 107% over ten years.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] Property prices have more than doubled over the past decade in the local areas around Abbey Wood station, with Abbey Wood seen as a 'buyer competition hotspot', with a +869% increase in buyer competition compared to ten years ago.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] There are currently major regeneration and development projects underway in that area of Abbey Wood and Thamesmead, which the Mayor of London has designated an 'Opportunity Area'.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] Thamesmead is currently undergoing an extensive regeneration project by Britain's oldest housing association Peabody, which promises up to 20,000 new homes, and improved community facilities.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] According to the 2021 census, Abbey Wood has a population of 17,700.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] 35.4% of residents are aged 0–24, above the borough average of 31.3%.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] The largest ethnic group is White, making up 46.3% of the population, below the borough average of 55.7%, with the second largest being Black/Black British being 33.1% of the population, above the borough average of 21.0%.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] The largest religious group in Abbey Wood is Christianity, making up 51.7% of the population, with the second largest being No religion, with 24.5% of the population.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] Places of interest include the ruins of the 12th-century Lesnes Abbey and the adjacent Lesnes Abbey Woods, a Local Nature Reserve.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] Part of the Woods are designated as a Site of Special Scientific Interest called Abbey Wood, which has important Paleogene fossils.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] The ancient Bostall Woods & Heath are part of the South East London Green Chain - a 40-mile, signposted network of footpaths link together many of the finest open spaces in South East London.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] This area includes one of the few camping and caravan sites in London, which is owned and operated by The Caravan Club.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] The co-operative woods were also the site of the first camp for the Woodcraft Folk.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] Michael and All Angels Parish Church was opened in a temporary building in 1905.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] A permanent church, designed by Sir Arthur Blomfield, was consecrated three years later, and the original building became the church hall.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] The 'Grade I' listed Victorian Crossness Pumping Station is described by architectural historian Nikolaus Pevsner as "a masterpiece of engineering – a Victorian cathedral of ironwork".
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] Abbey Wood has a number of parks and sports areas, including Bostall Gardens (play area, tennis courts and basketball court), Bostall Heath (cricket pitch, bowling green, orienteering, football pitch) and Abbey Wood Park (play area and football pitch).
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] It also has a women's netball team Abbey Angels.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] Abbey Wood Yoga offer yoga classes at St Paul's Academy, Bostall Gardens and pop-up events in and around Abbey Wood.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] Abbey Wood is part of the Erith and Thamesmead constituency for elections to the House of Commons of the United Kingdom, currently represented by Abena Oppong-Asare.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] Abbey Wood is part of the Abbey Wood ward for elections to Greenwich London Borough Council.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] Sir Charles Tilston Bright, the British electrical engineer who oversaw the laying of the first transatlantic telegraph cable in 1858, died in Abbey Wood in May 1888.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] William Morris lived at the nearby Red House, in Bexleyheath, a house which was built for him by the architect Philip Webb.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] Morris regularly walked to Abbey Wood station, and a plaque just off Knee Hill commemorates this association.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] Stewart Cochrane, a cruise ship bandleader, jazz musician, onetime member of NWOHM band Samson and author of *Chindit Special Force Burma 1944* attended DeLucy infant/primary school.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] Snooker champion Steve Davis lived in Commonwealth Way, Abbey Wood and went to Alexander McLeod Primary School and Abbey Wood Secondary School.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] Boxer Julius Francis went to St Thomas a Becket Primary School and Abbey Wood School, and Olympic runner Jennifer Stoute also went to Abbey Wood School.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] Playwright Jonathan Harvey also taught there.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] Kate Bush attended the convent school at the top of Knee Hill.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] Time 106.8, a licensed local radio station that evolved from an early cable channel - Radio Thamesmead - had studios on the Abbey Wood/Plumstead borders, and closed in April 2009.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] Abbey Wood also hosted London's first cable TV station, Cablevision, on Plumstead High Street, near Wickham Lane.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] The Thamesmead estate was the focus of an exhibition at RIBA to mark its 50th anniversary.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] "Thamesmead: A Town for the 21st Century" presented a series of archival images of Thamesmead, displayed alongside contemporary photographs of the estate's residents.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] The buildings have been utilised as a backdrop for many filmic projects, including the Stanley Kubrick film *A Clockwork Orange* and the video of "Come to Daddy" by electronic musician Aphex Twin.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] The 'Thamesmead Community Archive' is an online archive of material collected from local residents, Bexley Local Studies Archive, London Metropolitan Archive, the British Library, the RIBA archive and local authorities.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] 'Thamesmead Codex' by artist Bob and Roberta Smith was exhibited at Tate Modern in 2024–2026.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] The Lakeside Centre, situated on the edge of Southmere Lake, is home to a growing creative community, with 38 affordable artist studios, two artist in residence studios, a community darkroom and community garden.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] St Paul's Academy is a Roman Catholic secondary school located in the area, on the original site of the Abbey Wood comprehensive school.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] It was previously known as St Paul's RC Secondary School, whilst located in Wickham Lane, before converting to academy status in 2005 when it moved to the new site.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] Abbey Wood borders Thamesmead to the northwest, north and northeast, Belvedere to the east and southeast, West Heath.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] The Abbey Wood train station is located approximately 1.4 miles from the River Thames, between the Thames Barrier (3.5 miles to the West) and the Dartford Crossing (6 miles to the East).
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] The station became a terminus for the southeastern branch of the Crossrail-constructed Elizabeth line on 24 May 2022, providing services towards Canary Wharf, Liverpool Street, Bond Street, London Paddington and Heathrow Terminal 5.
[src:beam-engine/abbey-wood] The nearest station is Abbey Wood for Southeastern services towards Barnehurst, Crayford, Dartford, Gillingham, London Cannon Street and Charing Cross, and Thameslink services towards Luton.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] Although absolute zero can be approached, it cannot be reached.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] Some isentropic processes, such as adiabatic expansion, can lower the system's temperature without relying on a colder medium.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] Nevertheless, the third law of thermodynamics implies that no physical process can reach absolute zero in a finite number of steps.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] As a system nears this limit, further reductions in temperature become increasingly difficult, regardless of the cooling method used.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] In 2018, scientists at the University of Bremen achieved temperatures as low as 38 picokelvin (pK), 38 trillionths of a degree above absolute zero.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] At these low temperatures, matter displays exotic quantum mechanical phenomena such as superconductivity, superfluidity, and Bose–Einstein condensation.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] The particles still exhibit zero-point energy motion, as mandated by the Heisenberg uncertainty principle and, for a system of fermions, the Pauli exclusion principle.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] For an ideal gas, the pressure at constant volume decreases linearly with temperature, and the volume at constant pressure also decreases linearly with temperature.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] When these relationships are expressed using the Celsius scale, both pressure and volume extrapolate to zero at approximately −273.15 °C.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] This implies the existence of a lower bound on temperature, beyond which the gas would have negative pressure or volume—an unphysical result.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] To resolve this, the concept of absolute temperature is introduced, with 0 kelvins defined as the point at which pressure or volume would vanish in an ideal gas.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] This temperature corresponds to −273.15 °C, and is referred to as absolute zero.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] The ideal gas law is therefore formulated in terms of absolute temperature to remain consistent with observed gas behavior and physical limits.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] Absolute temperature is conventionally measured on the Kelvin scale (using Celsius-scaled increments) and, more rarely, on the Rankine scale (using Fahrenheit-scaled increments).
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] Absolute temperature measurement is uniquely determined by a multiplicative constant which specifies the size of the *degree*, so the *ratios* of two absolute temperatures, *T*2/*T*1, are the same in all scales.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] Absolute temperature also emerges naturally in statistical mechanics.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] In the Maxwell–Boltzmann, Fermi–Dirac, and Bose–Einstein distributions, absolute temperature appears in the exponential factor that determines how particles populate energy states.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] Specifically, the relative number of particles at a given energy *E* depends exponentially on *E/kT*, where *k* is the Boltzmann constant and *T* is the absolute temperature.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] The third law of thermodynamics concerns the behavior of entropy as temperature approaches absolute zero.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] It states that the entropy of a system approaches a constant minimum at 0 K.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] For a perfect crystal, this minimum is taken to be zero, since the system would be in a state of perfect order with only one microstate available.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] In some systems, there may be more than one microstate at minimum energy and there is some residual entropy at 0 K.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] Several other formulations of the third law exist.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] Nernst heat theorem holds that the change in entropy for any constant-temperature process tends to zero as the temperature approaches zero.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] A key consequence is that absolute zero cannot be reached, since removing heat becomes increasingly inefficient and entropy changes vanish.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] This unattainability principle means no physical process can cool a system to absolute zero in a finite number of steps or finite time.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] Using the Debye model, the specific heat and entropy of a pure crystal are proportional to *T* 3, while the enthalpy and chemical potential are proportional to *T* 4 (Guggenheim, p.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] These quantities drop toward their *T* = 0 limiting values and approach with *zero* slopes.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] For the specific heats at least, the limiting value itself is definitely zero, as borne out by experiments to below 10 K.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] Even the less detailed Einstein model shows this curious drop in specific heats.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] In fact, all specific heats vanish at absolute zero, not just those of crystals.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] Likewise for the coefficient of thermal expansion.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] Maxwell's relations show that various other quantities also vanish.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] One model that estimates the properties of an electron gas at absolute zero in metals is the Fermi gas.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] The electrons, being fermions, must be in different quantum states, which leads the electrons to get very high typical velocities, even at absolute zero.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] The maximum energy that electrons can have at absolute zero is called the Fermi energy.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] The Fermi temperature is defined as this maximum energy divided by the Boltzmann constant, and is on the order of 80,000 K for typical electron densities found in metals.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] For temperatures significantly below the Fermi temperature, the electrons behave in almost the same way as at absolute zero.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] This explains the failure of the classical equipartition theorem for metals that eluded classical physicists in the late 19th century.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] thus, as *T* decreases, Δ*G* and Δ*H* approach each other (so long as Δ*S* is bounded).
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] Experimentally, it is found that all spontaneous processes (including chemical reactions) result in a decrease in *G* as they proceed toward equilibrium.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] If Δ*S* and/or *T* are small, the condition Δ*G* < 0 may imply that Δ*H* < 0, which would indicate an exothermic reaction.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] However, this is not required; endothermic reactions can proceed spontaneously if the *T*Δ*S* term is large enough.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] Moreover, the slopes of the derivatives of Δ*G* and Δ*H* converge and are equal to zero at *T* = 0.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] Even at absolute zero, a quantum system retains a minimum amount of energy due to the Heisenberg uncertainty principle, which prevents particles from having both perfectly defined position and momentum.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] This residual energy is known as zero-point energy.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] In the case of the quantum harmonic oscillator, a standard model for vibrations in atoms and molecules, the uncertainty in a particle's momentum implies it must retain some kinetic energy, while the uncertainty in its position contributes to potential energy.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] As a result, such a system has a nonzero energy at absolute zero.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] Zero-point energy helps explain certain physical phenomena.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] For example, liquid helium does not solidify at normal pressure, even at temperatures near absolute zero.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] The large zero-point motion of helium atoms, caused by their low mass and weak interatomic forces, prevents them from settling into a solid structure.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] Only under high pressure does helium solidify, as the atoms are forced closer together and the interatomic forces grow stronger.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] One of the first to discuss the possibility of an absolute minimal temperature was Robert Boyle.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] His 1665 *New Experiments and Observations touching Cold*, articulated the dispute known as the *primum frigidum*.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] The concept was well known among naturalists of the time.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] Some contended an absolute minimum temperature occurred within earth (as one of the four classical elements), others within water, others air, and some more recently within nitre.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] The question of whether there is a limit to the degree of coldness possible, and, if so, where the zero must be placed, was first addressed by the French physicist Guillaume Amontons in 1703, in connection with his improvements in the air thermometer.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] His instrument indicated temperatures by the height at which a certain mass of air sustained a column of mercury—the pressure, or "spring" of the air varying with temperature.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] Amontons therefore argued that the zero of his thermometer would be that temperature at which the spring of the air was reduced to nothing.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] He used a scale that marked the boiling point of water at +73 and the melting point of ice at +51+1⁄2, so that the zero was equivalent to about −240 on the Celsius scale.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] Amontons held that the absolute zero cannot be reached, so never attempted to compute it explicitly.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] The value of −240 °C, or "431 divisions [in Fahrenheit's thermometer] below the cold of freezing water" was published by George Martine in 1740.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] This close approximation to the modern value of −273.15 °C for the zero of the air thermometer was further improved upon in 1779 by Johann Heinrich Lambert, who observed that −270 °C (−454.00 °F; 3.15 K) might be regarded as absolute cold.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] Values of this order for the absolute zero were not, however, universally accepted about this period.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] Pierre-Simon Laplace and Antoine Lavoisier, in their 1780 treatise on heat, arrived at values ranging from 1,500 to 3,000 below the freezing point of water, and thought that in any case it must be at least 600 below.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] John Dalton in his *Chemical Philosophy* gave ten calculations of this value, and finally adopted −3,000 °C as the natural zero of temperature.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] This suggested that the volume of a gas cooled at about −273 °C would reach zero.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] It followed from the principles on which this scale was constructed that its zero was placed at −273 °C, at almost precisely the same point as the zero of the air thermometer, where the air volume would reach "nothing".
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] This value was not immediately accepted; values ranging from −271.1 °C (−455.98 °F) to −274.5 °C (−462.10 °F), derived from laboratory measurements and observations of astronomical refraction, remained in use in the early 20th century.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] High-precision gas thermometry in the 1930s further narrowed the value.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] In 1937, Masao Kinoshita and Jiro Oishi reported measurements of expansion and pressure coefficients for nitrogen, hydrogen, helium, and neon, deriving the absolute temperature of 0 °C.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] The Tokyo Tech Museum and Archives later identified Kinoshita and Oishi's measurements, which gave a value close to 273.15 K for the ice point, as part of the experimental basis for the value adopted in 1954 thermometry discussions.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] With a better theoretical understanding of absolute zero, scientists were eager to reach this temperature in the lab.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] By 1845, Michael Faraday had managed to liquefy most gases then known to exist, and reached a new record for lowest temperatures by reaching −130 °C (−202 °F; 143 K).
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] Faraday believed that certain gases, such as oxygen, nitrogen, and hydrogen, were permanent gases and could not be liquefied.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] Decades later, in 1873 Dutch theoretical scientist Johannes Diderik van der Waals demonstrated that these gases could be liquefied, but only under conditions of very high pressure and very low temperatures.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] In 1877, Louis Paul Cailletet in France and Raoul Pictet in Switzerland succeeded in producing the first droplets of liquid air at −195 °C (−319.0 °F; 78.1 K).
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] This was followed in 1883 by the production of liquid oxygen −218 °C (−360.4 °F; 55.1 K) by the Polish professors Zygmunt Wróblewski and Karol Olszewski.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] Scottish chemist and physicist James Dewar and Dutch physicist Heike Kamerlingh Onnes took on the challenge to liquefy the remaining gases, hydrogen and helium.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] In 1898, after 20 years of effort, Dewar was the first to liquefy hydrogen, reaching a new low-temperature record of −252 °C (−421.6 °F; 21.1 K).
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] However, Kamerlingh Onnes, his rival, was the first to liquefy helium, in 1908, using several precooling stages and the Hampson–Linde cycle.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] He lowered the temperature to the boiling point of helium −269 °C (−452.20 °F; 4.15 K).
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] By reducing the pressure of the liquid helium, he achieved an even lower temperature, near 1.5 K.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] These were the coldest temperatures achieved on Earth at the time and his achievement earned him the Nobel Prize in 1913.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] Kamerlingh Onnes would continue to study the properties of materials at temperatures near absolute zero, describing superconductivity and superfluids for the first time.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] Temperatures below zero on the Celsius or Fahrenheit scales are simply colder than the zero points of those scales.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] In contrast, certain isolated systems can achieve negative thermodynamic temperatures (in kelvins), which are not colder than absolute zero, but paradoxically hotter than any positive temperature.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] If a negative-temperature system and a positive-temperature system come in contact, heat flows from the negative to the positive-temperature system.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] Negative temperatures can only occur in systems that have an upper limit to the energy they can contain.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] In these cases, adding energy can decrease entropy, reversing the usual relationship between energy and temperature.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] This leads to a negative thermodynamic temperature.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] However, such conditions only arise in specialized, quasi-equilibrium systems such as collections of spins in a magnetic field.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] In contrast, ordinary systems with translational or vibrational motion have no upper energy limit, so their temperatures are always positive.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] The average temperature of the universe today is approximately 2.73 K (−270.42 °C; −454.76 °F), based on measurements of cosmic microwave background radiation.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] Standard models of the future expansion of the universe predict that the average temperature of the universe is decreasing over time.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] This temperature is calculated as the mean density of energy in space; it should not be confused with the mean electron temperature (total energy divided by particle count) which has increased over time.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] Absolute zero cannot be achieved, although it is possible to reach temperatures close to it through the use of evaporative cooling, cryocoolers, dilution refrigerators, and nuclear adiabatic demagnetization.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] The use of laser cooling has produced temperatures of less than a billionth of a kelvin.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] At very low temperatures in the vicinity of absolute zero, matter exhibits many unusual properties, including superconductivity, superfluidity, and Bose–Einstein condensation.
[src:beam-engine/absolute-zero] To study such phenomena, scientists have worked to obtain even lower temperatures.
[src:beam-engine/addington-london] In Domesday Book of 1086, the area was named *Edintona* and then *Eddintone*.
[src:beam-engine/addington-london] The village lay within the Wallington hundred in the county of Surrey.
[src:beam-engine/addington-london] Addington is thought to be named after Edda, a Saxon landowner.
[src:beam-engine/addington-london] In Domesday, two manors are mentioned, linked with the names Godric and Osward.
[src:beam-engine/addington-london] Addington Place, later known as Addington Farm and now called Addington Palace, dominates the village above the church of St Mary the Blessed Virgin Church and *The Cricketers* pub.
[src:beam-engine/addington-london] The manor house was situated behind the church and was the residence of the Leigh family.
[src:beam-engine/addington-london] There is an oft repeated, but false account of a royal hunting lodge, "where King Henry VIII supposedly wooed Anne Boleyn, whose family owned nearby Wickham Court" by West Wickham Parish Church.
[src:beam-engine/addington-london] However, the Anne Boleyn of Wickham Court was the aunt of Queen Anne.
[src:beam-engine/addington-london] The Palladian Palace was built in 1780 by Barlow Trecothick, from Boston, Massachusetts in the colonial Province of Massachusetts Bay, who returned to England and became an MP and Lord Mayor of the City of London in 1770.
[src:beam-engine/addington-london] After his death without heirs, his nephew James Ivers (later Trecothick), also of Boston, continued his uncle's work and had the grounds laid out by Capability Brown.
[src:beam-engine/addington-london] The estate was sold and eventually, as Croydon Palace became too inconvenient and unsanitary, the Addington house and part of the estate was bought for the Archbishops of Canterbury as a country residence.
[src:beam-engine/addington-london] The last archbishop to use it was Edward Benson (Archbishop 1883–1896).
[src:beam-engine/addington-london] From 1954 to 1996, Addington Palace was the headquarters of the Royal School of Church Music.
[src:beam-engine/addington-london] Around 1805 parts of the estate covering what is now New Addington were sold to John Cator of Beckenham Place, including Castle Hill Farm.
[src:beam-engine/addington-london] Cator left this to George and Henry Sparkes in his Will in 1806, citing "Addington recently acquired from .....
[src:beam-engine/addington-london] Trecothick" but the land appears as part of the Cator estates in a private act of Parliament, Cator's Estate Act 1825 (6 Geo.
[src:beam-engine/addington-london] *38* Pr.) allowing the Cators to sell the land, as John Barwell Cator was transferring the main estate holdings to Woodbastwick in Norfolk.
[src:beam-engine/addington-london] In the 20th century, technological advances and population growth in the region led to many changes in the way of life for people in Addington.
[src:beam-engine/addington-london] At the beginning of the century, Addington was in the county of Surrey, which had established urban and rural districts to provide services matched to the needs of the differing communities.
[src:beam-engine/addington-london] The parish of Addington was transferred to Godstone Rural District on abolition of Croydon Rural District in 1915.
[src:beam-engine/addington-london] Subsequently, Addington parish became part of the County Borough of Croydon in 1925.
[src:beam-engine/addington-london] On 1 April 1928 the parish was abolished and merged with Croydon St John the Baptist.
[src:beam-engine/addington-london] At the 1921 census (the last before the abolition of the parish), Addington had a population of 691.
[src:beam-engine/addington-london] Since 1965 the county borough has been part of the London Borough of Croydon within highly urbanized Greater London.
[src:beam-engine/addington-london] New Addington was developed to the south of the existing village from the 1930s onwards.
[src:beam-engine/addington-london] There are still several old houses and buildings in Addington and, even though there has been some fairly modern building, the village atmosphere is intact in the 21st century, despite its being in Greater London.
[src:beam-engine/addington-london] There is a blacksmith's forge, dating from around 1740, now mainly making ornamental ironwork.
[src:beam-engine/addington-london] The hunt used to meet outside the pub, *The Cricketers* which has reverted to its former name once again after a temporary change of name.
[src:beam-engine/addington-london] The village co-operative store and post office is now a private house.
[src:beam-engine/addington-london] St Mary's Church, Addington is an Anglican church in the village.
[src:beam-engine/addington-london] It is associated with the Archbishops of Canterbury of the 19th century, who lived at nearby Addington Palace.
[src:beam-engine/addington-london] Five successive archbishops are buried at the church: Charles Manners-Sutton (d.1828); William Howley (d.1848); John Bird Sumner (d.1862); Charles Longley (d.1868); and Archibald Campbell Tait (d.1882).
[src:beam-engine/addington-london] Addington Village Interchange (also known as Addington Village tram stop) connects the area with Tramlink services to West Croydon and New Addington.
[src:beam-engine/addington-london] Addington Palace is served by Gravel Hill tram stop on the same line.
[src:beam-engine/addington-london] The interchange also provides access to bus routes run by Transport for London, which connect it with areas including Bromley, Croydon, Eltham, Hayes, New Addington, Orpington, Purley and Thornton Heath.
[src:beam-engine/addington-london] Cricket has been played in the village since at least the 18th century.
[src:beam-engine/addington-london] The Addington Golf Club is regarded as an important golf facility in the London area.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Steam power has generally been superseded by the internal combustion engine or by electrical power drawn from an electrical grid.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The only steam installations that are in widespread use are the highly efficient thermal power plants used for generating electricity on a large scale.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] In contrast, the proposed steam engines may be for stationary, road, rail, or marine use.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Although most references to "Modern Steam" apply to developments since the 1970s, certain aspects of advanced steam technology can be discerned throughout the 20th century, notably automatic boiler control along with rapid startup.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] In 1922, Abner Doble developed an electro-mechanical system that reacted simultaneously to steam temperature and pressure, starting and stopping the feed pumps whilst igniting and cutting out the burner according to boiler pressure.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The contraflow monotube boiler had a working pressure of 750–1,200 psi (5.17–8.27 MPa) but contained so little water in circulation as to present no risk of explosion.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] This type of boiler was continuously developed in the US, Britain and Germany throughout the 1930s and into the 1950s for use in cars, buses, trucks, railcars, shunting locomotives (US; switchers), a speedboat and, in 1933, a converted Travel Air 2000 biplane.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] In the UK, Sentinel Waggon Works developed a vertical water-tube boiler running at 275 psi (1.90 MPa) which was used in road vehicles, shunting locomotives and railcars.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Steam could be raised much more quickly than with a conventional locomotive boiler.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Trials of the Anderson condensing system took place on Britain's Southern Railway between 1930 and 1935.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The Anderson condensing system uses a process known as mechanical vapor recompression.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] It was devised by a Glasgow marine engineer, Harry Percival Harvey Anderson.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The theory was that, by removing around 600 of the 970 British thermal units present in each pound of steam (1400 of the 2260 kilojoules in each kilogram), it would be possible to return the exhaust steam to the boiler by a pump which would consume only 1–2% of the engine's power output.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Between 1925 and 1927 Anderson, and another Glasgow engineer John McCullum (some sources give McCallum), conducted experiments on a stationary steam plant with encouraging results.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] A company, Steam Heat Conservation (SHC), was formed and a demonstration of Anderson's system was arranged at Surbiton Electricity Generating Station.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] SHC was interested in applying the system to a railway locomotive and contacted Richard Maunsell of the Southern Railway.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Maunsell requested that a controlled test be carried out at Surbiton and this was done about 1929.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Maunsell's technical assistant, Harold Holcroft, was present and a fuel saving of 29% was recorded, compared to conventional atmospheric working.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The Southern Railway converted SECR N class locomotive number A816 (later 1816 and 31816) to the Anderson system in 1930.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The locomotive underwent trials and initial results were encouraging.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The trials continued until 1934 but various problems arose, mostly with the fan for forced draught, and the project went no further.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The locomotive was converted back to standard form in 1935.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The work of French mechanical engineer André Chapelon in applying scientific analysis and a strive for thermal efficiency was an early example of advanced steam technology.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Chapelon's protégé Livio Dante Porta continued Chapelon's work.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Postwar in the late 1940s and 1950s some designers worked on modernising steam locomotives.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The Argentinian engineer Livio Dante Porta in the development of Stephensonian railway locomotives incorporating advanced steam technology was a precursor of the 'Modern Steam' movement from 1948.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Where possible, Porta much preferred to design new locomotives, but more often in practice he was forced to radically update old ones to incorporate the new technology.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] 1949 by Oliver Bulleid and the British Rail ‘Standard’ class steam locomotives of the 1950s by Robert Riddles, particularly the BR Standard Class 9F, were used to trial new steam locomotive design features, including the Franco-Crosti boiler.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] On moving to Ireland, Bulleid also designed CIÉ No.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The Sir Biscoe Tritton Lecture, given by Roger Waller, of the DLM company to the Institute of Mechanical Engineers in 2003 gives an idea of how problems in steam power are being addressed.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Waller refers mainly to some rack and pinion mountain railway locomotives that were newly built from 1992 to 1998.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] They were developed for three companies in Switzerland and Austria and continued to work on two of these lines as of 2008.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The new steam locomotives burn the same grade of light oil as their diesel counterparts, and all demonstrate the same advantages of ready availability and reduced labour cost; at the same time, they have been shown to greatly reduce air and ground pollution.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Their economic superiority has meant that they have largely replaced the diesel locomotives and railcars previously operating the line; additionally, steam locomotives are a tourist attraction.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] A parallel line of development was the return to steam power of the old Lake Geneva paddle steamer *Montreux* that had been refitted with a diesel-electric engine in the 1960s.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Economic aims similar to those achieved with the rack locomotives were pursued through automatic control of the light-oil-fired boiler and remote control of the engine from the bridge, enabling the steamship to be operated by a crew of the same size as a motor ship.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] A power unit based on advanced steam technology burning fossil fuel will inevitably emit carbon dioxide, a long-lasting greenhouse gas.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] However, significant reductions of other pollutants such as CO and NOx are achievable by steam compared to other combustion technologies, since it does not involve explosive combustion, thus removing the need for add-ons (such as filters) or special preparation of fuel.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] If renewable fuel such as wood or other biofuel is used then the system could be carbon neutral.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The use of biofuel remains controversial; however, liquid biofuels are easier to manufacture for steam plant than for diesels as they do not demand the stringent fuel standards required to protect diesel injectors.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] In principle, combustion and power delivery of steam plant can be considered separate stages.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] High overall thermal efficiency may be difficult to achieve, largely due to the extra stage of generating a working fluid between combustion and power delivery attributable mainly to leakages and heat losses.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The separation of the processes allows specific problems to be addressed at each stage without revising the whole system every time.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] For instance, the boiler or steam generator can be adapted to use any heat source, whether obtained from solid, liquid or gaseous fuel, and can use waste heat.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Whatever the choice, it will have no direct effect on the design of the engine unit, as that only ever has to deal with steam.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] This project mainly includes combined electrical generation and heating systems for private homes and small villages burning wood or bamboo chips.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] This is intended to replace 2-stroke donkey engines and small diesel power plants.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Drastic reduction in noise level is one immediate benefit of a steam-powered small plant.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Ted Pritchard, of Melbourne, Australia, was intensively developing this type of unit from 2002 until his death in 2007.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The company Pritchard Power (now Uniflow Power) stated in 2010 that they continue to develop the stationary S5000, and that a prototype had been built and was being tested, and designs were being refined for market ready products.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Until 2006 a German company called *Enginion* was actively developing a *Steamcell*, a micro CHP unit about the size of a PC tower for domestic use.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] It seems that by 2008 it had merged with Berlin company AMOVIS.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Since 2012, a French company, EXOES, is selling to industrial firms a Rankine Cycle, patented, engine, which is designed to work with many fuels such as concentrated solar power, biomass, or fossil.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The system, called "SHAPE" for Sustainable Heat And Power Engine, converts the heat into electricity.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The SHAPE engine is suitable for embedded, and stationary, applications.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] A SHAPE engine has been integrated into a biomass boiler, and into a Concentrated solar power system.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The company is planning to work with automobile manufactures, long-haul truck manufactures, and railway corporations.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] A similar unit is marketed by Powertherm, a subsidiary of Spilling (see below).
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] A company in India manufactures steam-powered generators in a range of sizes from 4 hp to 50 hp.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] They also offer a number of different mills that can be powered by their engines.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] In matter of technology, notice that the Quasiturbine is a uniflow rotary steam engine where steam intakes in hot areas, while exhausting in cold areas.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The Spilling company produces a variety of small fixed stationary plant adapted to biomass combustion or power derived from waste heat or pressure recovery.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The Finnish company Steammotor Finland has developed a small rotary steam engine that runs with 800 kW steam generator.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The engines are planned to produce electricity in wood chip fired power plants.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] According to the company, the steam engine named *Quadrum* generates 27% efficiency and runs with 180 °C steam at 8 bar pressure, while a corresponding steam turbine produces just 15% efficiency, requires steam temperature of 240 °C and pressure of 40 bar.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The high efficiency comes from a patented crank mechanism, that gives a smooth, pulseless torque.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The company believes that by further developing the construction there is potential to reach as high efficiency as 30–35%.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] During the first 1970s oil crisis, a number of investigations into steam technology were initiated by large automobile corporations although as the crisis died down, impetus was soon lost.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Australian engineer Ted Pritchard's main field of research from the late 1950s until the 1970s was the building of several efficient steam power units working on the uniflow system adapted to a small truck and two cars.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] One of the cars was achieving the lowest emissions figures of that time.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] All these engines made heavy use of flameless ceramic heat cells both for the steam generator and at strategic boost points where steam was injected into the cylinder(s).
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] A design mounted on power bogies with compact water-tube boiler similar to Sentinel designs of the 1930s.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Example: Sentinel-Cammell locomotive (right).
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Both 52 8055 and the proposed 5AT are of conventional layout, with the cab at the back, while the ACE 3000 had the cab located at the front.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Other approaches are possible, especially with liquid fuel firing.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] This is a well-tried design with the potential for a large power output and would provide the driver good visibility.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Another well-tried design with large power potential.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] A future design could include shorter water tanks, and a cab at each end, to give the driver a good view in either direction.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Another proposal for advanced steam technology is to revive the fireless locomotive, which runs on stored steam independently pre-generated.
[src:beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] An example is the Solar Steam Train project in Sacramento, California.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam was founded at the mouth of the Amstel river, which was dammed to control flooding.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Originally a small fishing village in the 12th century, Amsterdam became a major world port during the Dutch Golden Age of the 17th century, when the Netherlands was an economic powerhouse.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam was the leading centre for finance and trade, as well as a hub of secular art production.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] In the 19th and 20th centuries, the city expanded and new neighborhoods and suburbs were built.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The city has a long tradition of openness, liberalism, and tolerance.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Cycling is key to the city's modern character, and there are numerous biking paths and lanes spread throughout.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The city is known for its nightlife and festival activity, with several nightclubs among the world's most famous.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Its artistic heritage, canals, and narrow canal houses with gabled façades, well-preserved legacies of the city's 17th-century Golden Age, have attracted millions of visitors annually.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The Amsterdam Stock Exchange, founded in 1602, is considered the oldest "modern" securities market stock exchange in the world.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] As the commercial capital of the Netherlands and one of the top financial centres in Europe, Amsterdam is considered an alpha-world city.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The city is the cultural capital of the Netherlands.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Many large Dutch institutions have their headquarters in the city.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Many of the world's largest companies are based in Amsterdam or have established their European headquarters there, such as technology companies Uber, Netflix, and Tesla.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Although Amsterdam is the official capital of the Netherlands, it is not the seat of government.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The main governmental institutions, and foreign embassies, are located in The Hague.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] In 2022, Amsterdam was ranked the ninth-best city to live in by the Economist Intelligence Unit and 12th on quality of living for environment and infrastructure by Mercer.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The city was ranked 4th place globally as a top tech hub in 2019.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The Port of Amsterdam is the fifth largest in Europe.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The KLM hub and Amsterdam's main airport, Schiphol, is the busiest airport in the Netherlands, and third in Europe.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The Dutch capital is one of the most multicultural cities in the world, with about 180 nationalities represented.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Immigration and ethnic segregation in Amsterdam is a current issue.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam's notable residents throughout its history include painters Rembrandt and Vincent van Gogh, 17th-century philosophers Baruch Spinoza, John Locke, René Descartes, and John Amos Comenius, and Holocaust victim and diarist Anne Frank.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Due to its geographical location in what used to be wet peatland, the founding of Amsterdam is later than other urban centres in the Low Countries.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] However, around the area of what later became Amsterdam, farmers settled as early as three millennia ago.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] They lived along the prehistoric IJ river and upstream of its tributary Amstel.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The prehistoric IJ was a shallow and quiet stream in peatland behind beach ridges.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] This secluded area was able to grow into an important local settlement centre, especially in the late Bronze Age, the Iron Age and the Roman Age.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Until water issues were controlled, a permanent settlement would not have been possible, since the river mouth and the banks of the Amstel in this period in time were too wet for permanent habitation.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The origins of Amsterdam are linked to the development of a dam on the Amstel River called *Amestelle*, meaning 'watery area', from *Aa(m)* 'river' + *stelle* 'site at a shoreline', 'river bank'.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] In this area, land reclamation started as early as the late 10th century.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Amestelle was located along a side arm of the IJ.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] This sidearm took its name from the eponymous land: Amstel.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Amestelle was inhabited by farmers, who lived more inland and more upstream, where the land was not as wet as at the banks of the downstream river mouth.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] These farmers were starting the reclamation around upstream Ouderkerk aan de Amstel, and later at the other side of the river at Amstelveen.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The Van Amstel family, known in documents by this name since 1019, held the stewardship in this northwestern nook of the ecclesiastical district of the bishop of Utrecht.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The family later served also under the count of Holland.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] A major turning point in the development of the Amstel River mouth was the All Saint's Flood of 1170.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] In an extremely short time, the shallow river IJ turned into a wide estuary, which from then on offered the Amstel an open connection to the Zuiderzee, IJssel, and waterways further afield.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] This made the water flow of the Amstel more active, so excess water could be drained better.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] With drier banks, the downstream Amstel mouth became attractive for permanent habitation.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Moreover, the river had grown from an insignificant peat stream into a junction of international waterways.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] A settlement was built here immediately after the landscape change of 1170.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Right from the start of its foundation it focused on traffic, production, and trade; not on farming, as opposed to how communities had lived further upstream for the past 200 years and northward for thousands of years.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The construction of a dam at the mouth of the Amstel, eponymously named Dam, is historically estimated to have occurred between 1264 and 1275.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The settlement first appeared in a document from 1275, concerning a road toll granted by the count of Holland Floris V to the residents *apud Amestelledamme* 'at the dam in the Amstel' or 'at the dam of Amstelland'.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] This allowed the inhabitants of the village to travel freely through the County of Holland, paying no tolls at bridges, locks and dams.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] This was a move in a years-long struggle for power in the area between the count of Holland and the Amstel family who governed the area on behalf of the bishop of Utrecht.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] By 1327, the name had developed into *Aemsterdam*.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The bishop of Utrecht granted Amsterdam zone rights in either 1300 or 1306.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The Mirakel van Amsterdam in 1345 rendered the city an important place of pilgrimage.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] During the heyday of the *Stille Omgang*, which became the expression of the pilgrimage after the Protestant Reformation, up to 90,000 pilgrims came to Amsterdam.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] From the 14th century on, Amsterdam flourished, largely from trade with the Hanseatic League.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] From the 15th century on the city established an independent trade route with the Baltic Sea in grain and timber, cutting out the Hanseatic League as middlemen.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The city became the staple market of Europe for bulk cargo.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] This was made possible due to innovations in the herring fishery, from which Amsterdam reaped great wealth.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Herring had demand in markets all around Europe.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Inventions of on-board gibbing and the haringbuis in 1415, made longer voyages feasible and hence enabled Dutch fishermen to follow the herring shoals far from the coasts, giving them a monopoly in the industry.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The herring industry relied on international trade cooperation and large initial investments in ships.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] This required many highly skilled and unskilled workers to cooperate, as well as the import of the necessary raw materials to turn an unfinished product into a marketable one.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] This required merchants to then sell it throughout the continent and bookkeepers and accountants to divide the profit.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] In short, the herring industry was setting up the foundations for what would later become the transcontinental trade system and the Dutch Golden Age, with Amsterdam at its centre, hence the saying "Amsterdam is built on Herringbones".
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The Low Countries were part of the Habsburg inheritance and came under the Spanish Empire in the early sixteenth century.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The Dutch rebelled against Philip II of Spain, who led a defense of Catholicism during the Protestant Reformation.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The main reasons for the uprising were the imposition of new taxes, the tenth penny, and the religious persecution of Protestants by the newly introduced Inquisition.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The revolt escalated into the Eighty Years' War, which ultimately led to Dutch independence.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Strongly pushed by Dutch Revolt leader William the Silent, the Dutch Republic became known for its relative religious tolerance.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Jews from the Iberian Peninsula, Protestant Huguenots from France, prosperous merchants, and printers from Flanders, and economic and religious refugees from the Spanish-controlled parts of the Low Countries found safety in Amsterdam.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The influx of Flemish printers and the city's intellectual tolerance made Amsterdam a centre for the European free press.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] During the 17th century, Amsterdam experienced what is considered its *Golden Age*, during which it became the wealthiest city in the Western world.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Ships sailed from Amsterdam to the Baltic Sea, the Caribbean, North America, and Africa, as well as present-day Indonesia, India, Sri Lanka, and Brazil, forming the basis of a worldwide trading network.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam's merchants had the largest share in both the Dutch East India Company (VOC) and the Dutch West India Company.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] These companies acquired overseas possessions that later became Dutch colonies.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam was Europe's most important hub for the shipment of goods and was the leading financial centre of the Western world.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] In 1602, the Amsterdam office of the Dutch East India Company became the world's first stock exchange by trading in its own shares.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The Bank of Amsterdam started operations in 1609, acting as a full-service bank for Dutch merchant bankers and as a reserve bank.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] From the 17th century onwards, Amsterdam also became involved in the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The city was a major destination port for Dutch slave ships participating in the triangular trade, which lasted until the United Netherlands abolished the Netherlands' involvement in the trade in 1814 at the request of the British government.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam's prosperity declined during the 18th and early 19th centuries.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The wars of the Dutch Republic with England (latterly, Great Britain) and France took their toll on the city.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] During the French Revolutionary Wars and the Napoleonic Wars, Amsterdam's significance reached its lowest point, with Holland being absorbed into the French Empire.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] However, the later establishment of the United Kingdom of the Netherlands in 1815 marked a turning point.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The end of the 19th century is sometimes called Amsterdam's second Golden Age.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] New museums, a railway station, and the Concertgebouw were built; At the same time, the Industrial Revolution reached the city.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The Amsterdam–Rhine Canal was dug to give Amsterdam a direct connection to the Rhine, and the North Sea Canal was dug to give the port a shorter connection to the North Sea.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Both projects dramatically improved commerce with the rest of Europe and the world.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] In 1906, Joseph Conrad gave a brief description of Amsterdam as seen from the seaside, in *The Mirror of the Sea*.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Shortly before the First World War, the city started to expand again, and new suburbs were built.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Even though the Netherlands remained neutral in this war, Amsterdam suffered a food shortage, and heating fuel became scarce.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The shortages sparked riots in which several people were killed.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] These riots are known as the *Aardappeloproer* (Potato Rebellion).
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] People started looting stores and warehouses to get supplies, mainly food.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] On 1 January 1921, after a flood in 1916, the depleted municipalities of Durgerdam, Holysloot, Zunderdorp and Schellingwoude (all lying north of Amsterdam) were, at their own request, annexed to the city.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Between the wars, the city continued to expand, most notably to the west of the Jordaan district in the Frederik Hendrikbuurt and surrounding neighbourhoods.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Nazi Germany invaded the Netherlands on 10 May 1940 and took control of the country.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Some Amsterdam citizens sheltered Jews, thereby exposing themselves and their families to a high risk of being imprisoned or sent to concentration camps.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] More than 100,000 Dutch Jews were deported and murdered in Nazi concentration camps, including 56,521 victims in Auschwitz and a further number of 34,082 accounted for in Sobibor.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Around 60,000 Jewish inhabitants, including Jewish prewar refugees from Austria and Germany, were living in Amsterdam at the time of the Nazi occupation.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Only those provided with a safe haven, avoiding deportation and denunciation, or the very few who returned from the camps at the end of the war, managed to survive.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] At first the German occupation authorities were very cautious, wanting to convince the city inhabitants of their sincerity.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] However, their outlook soon turned to cynicism and brutality.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] A cause in the change of their behaviour was an attack by a Dutch resistance fighter against a collaborator belonging to the paramilitary Dutch fascist organisation, the NSB.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The injured man died and in response Heinrich Himmler ordered reprisals.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] 427 Amsterdam Jews were arrested on 22 February 1941 and sent to Mauthausen concentration camp.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Incensed, a broad spectrum of passive resistance was organized by the Dutch Underground.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Trade unions, among them socialist and Communist Party activists, led the protest.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Their outcry received support from white collar employees in the civil service and support from the local diocese of the Church.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Approval was also given and encouraged by the Dutch government-in-exile under Queen Wilhelmina in London.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The German authorities were taken completely by surprise by the level of resistance known as the February strike.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] 300,000 people participated in the protest against the arrests of Jews.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] However, the occupier soon responded crudely and brutally, smashing union and illegal party activity.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] With the edifice of resistance removed the SS and German police apparatus, supported by collaborators in the Dutch auxiliary police, arrested thousands of defenceless Jews in Amsterdam's Jewish Quarter.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The two main waves of arrest, culminating in deportation, occurred on 26 May 1943 and on 20 June 1943.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The most famous deportee was the young Jewish girl Anne Frank, whose safe hiding place with her family was betrayed and discovered in August, 1944.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] After a spell at the 'holding camp' in Westerbork Anna and her family were sent to Auschwitz, where her mother was murdered.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] From there she and her sister Margot were moved onto Bergen-Belsen concentration camp where they died amidst appalling and inhumane conditions in early 1945.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] At the end of the Second World War, and as a consequence of the Nazi occupation, Amsterdam was in a state of crisis.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Communication with the rest of the country broke down, and food and fuel became scarce.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Many citizens traveled to the countryside to forage.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Dogs, cats, raw sugar beets, and tulip bulbs—cooked to a pulp—were consumed to stay alive.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Many trees in Amsterdam were cut down for fuel, and wood was taken from the houses, apartments and other buildings of deported Jews.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The city was finally liberated by Canadian forces on 5 May 1945, shortly before the end of the war in Europe.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Many new suburbs, such as Osdorp, Slotervaart, Slotermeer and Geuzenveld, were built in the years after the Second World War.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] These suburbs contained many public parks and wide-open spaces, and the new buildings provided improved housing conditions with larger and brighter rooms, gardens, and balconies.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Because of the war and other events of the 20th century, almost the entire city centre had fallen into disrepair.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] As society was changing, politicians and other influential figures made plans to redesign large parts of it.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] There was an increasing demand for office buildings, and also for new roads, as the automobile became available to most people.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] A metro started operating in 1977 between the new suburb of Bijlmermeer in the city's Zuidoost (southeast) exclave and the centre of Amsterdam.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Further plans were to build a new highway above the metro to connect Amsterdam Centraal and the city centre with other parts of the city.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The required large-scale demolitions began in Amsterdam's former Jewish neighborhood.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Smaller streets, such as the Jodenbreestraat and Weesperstraat, were widened and almost all houses and buildings were demolished.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] At the peak of the demolition, the *Nieuwmarktrellen* (Nieuwmarkt riots) broke out; the rioters expressed their fury about the demolition caused by the restructuring of the city.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] As a result, the demolition was stopped and the highway into the city's centre was never fully built; only the metro was completed.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The new city hall was built on the almost completely demolished Waterlooplein.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Meanwhile, large private organizations, such as *Stadsherstel Amsterdam*, were founded to restore the entire city centre.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Although the success of this struggle is visible today, efforts for further restoration are still ongoing.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The entire city centre has reattained its former splendour and, as a whole, is now a protected area.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Many of its buildings have become monuments, and in July 2010 the Grachtengordel (the three concentric canals: Herengracht, Keizersgracht, and Prinsengracht) was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] In the 21st century, the Amsterdam city centre has attracted large numbers of tourists: between 2012 and 2015, the annual number of visitors rose from 10 to 17 million.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Real estate prices have surged, and local shops are making way for tourist-oriented ones, making the centre unaffordable for the city's inhabitants.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] These developments have evoked comparisons with Venice, a city thought to be overwhelmed by the tourist influx.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Construction of a new metro line connecting the part of the city north of the IJ to its southern part was started in 2003.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The project was controversial because its cost had exceeded its budget by a factor of three by 2008, because of fears of damage to buildings in the centre, and because construction had to be halted and restarted multiple times.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The new metro line was completed in 2018.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Since 2014, renewed focus has been given to urban regeneration and renewal, especially in areas directly bordering the city centre, such as Frederik Hendrikbuurt.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] This urban renewal and expansion of the traditional centre of the city—with the construction of artificial islands of the new eastern IJburg neighbourhood—is part of the Structural Vision Amsterdam 2040 initiative.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam is located in the Western Netherlands, in the province of North Holland, the capital of which is not Amsterdam, but rather Haarlem.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The river Amstel ends in the city centre and connects to a large number of canals that eventually terminate in the IJ.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam's elevation is about −2 m (−6.6 ft) below sea level.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The surrounding land is flat as it is formed of large polders.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] An artificial forest, Amsterdamse Bos, is in the southwest.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam is connected to the North Sea by the North Sea Canal.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam is intensely urbanised, as is the Metropolitan Region Amsterdam surrounding the city.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Comprising 219.4 km2 (84.7 sq mi) of land, the city proper has 4,457 inhabitants per km2 and 2,275 houses per km2.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Parks and nature reserves make up 12% of Amsterdam's land area.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam has more than 100 km (60 mi) of canals, most of which are navigable by boat.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The city's three main canals are the Prinsengracht, the Herengracht, and the Keizersgracht.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] In the Middle Ages, Amsterdam was surrounded by a moat, called the Singel, which now forms the innermost ring in the city, and gives the city centre a horseshoe shape.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] It has been compared with Venice, due to its division into about 90 islands, which are linked by more than 1,200 bridges.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam has an oceanic climate (Köppen: *Cfb*) strongly influenced by its proximity to the North Sea to the west, with prevailing westerly winds.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam, as well as most of the North Holland province, lies in USDA Hardiness zone 8b.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Frosts mainly occur during spells of easterly or northeasterly winds from the inner European continent.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Even then, because Amsterdam is surrounded on three sides by large bodies of water, as well as having a significant heat-island effect, nights rarely fall below −5 °C (23 °F), while it could easily be −12 °C (10 °F) in Hilversum, 25 km (16 mi) southeast.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Summers are moderately warm with several hot and humid days with occasional rain every month.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The average daily high in August is 22.1 °C (72 °F), and 30 °C (86 °F) or higher is only measured on average on 2.5 days, placing Amsterdam in AHS Heat Zone 2.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Days with more than 1 mm (0.04 in) of precipitation are common, on average 133 days per year.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam's average annual precipitation is 838 mm (33 in).
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] A large part of this precipitation falls as light rain or brief showers.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Cloudy and damp days are common during the cooler months of October through March.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] In 1300, Amsterdam's population was around 1,000 people.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] While many towns in Holland experienced population decline during the 15th and 16th centuries, Amsterdam's population grew, mainly due to the rise of the profitable Baltic maritime trade especially in grain after the Burgundian victory in the Dutch–Hanseatic War in 1441.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The population of Amsterdam was only modest compared to the towns and cities of Flanders and Brabant, which comprised the most urbanized area of the Low Countries.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] This changed when, during the Dutch Revolt, many people from the Southern Netherlands fled to the North, especially after Antwerp fell to Spanish forces in 1585.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Jews from Spain, Portugal, and Eastern Europe similarly settled in Amsterdam, as did Germans and Scandinavians.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] In thirty years, Amsterdam's population more than doubled between 1585 and 1610.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] During the 1660s, Amsterdam's population reached 200,000.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The city's growth levelled off and the population stabilized around 240,000 for most of the 18th century.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] In 1750, Amsterdam was the fourth largest city in Western Europe, behind London (676,000), Paris (560,000) and Naples (324,000).
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] This was all the more remarkable as Amsterdam was neither the capital city nor the seat of government of the Dutch Republic, which itself was a much smaller state than Great Britain, France or the Ottoman Empire.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] In contrast to those other metropolises, Amsterdam was also surrounded by large towns such as Leiden (about 67,000), Rotterdam (45,000), Haarlem (38,000), and Utrecht (30,000).
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The city's population declined in the early 19th century, dipping under 200,000 in 1820.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] By the second half of the 19th century, industrialization spurred renewed growth.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam's population hit an all-time high of 872,000 in 1959, before declining in the following decades due to government-sponsored suburbanisation to so-called *groeikernen* (growth centres) such as Purmerend and Almere.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Between 1970 and 1980, Amsterdam experienced a sharp population decline, peaking at a net loss of 25,000 people in 1973.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] By 1985 the city had only 675,570 residents.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] This was soon followed by reurbanization and gentrification, leading to renewed population growth in the 2010s.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Also in the 2010s, much of Amsterdam's population growth was due to immigration to the city.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] In the 16th and 17th centuries, non-Dutch immigrants to Amsterdam were mostly Protestant Huguenots and Flemings, Sephardic Jews, and Westphalians.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Huguenots came after the Edict of Fontainebleau in 1685, while the Flemish Protestants came during the Eighty Years' War against Catholic Spain.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The Westphalians came to Amsterdam mostly for economic reasons; their influx continued through the 18th and 19th centuries.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Before the Second World War, 10% of the city population was Jewish.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Just twenty percent of them survived the Holocaust.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam experienced an influx of religions and cultures after the Second World War.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] With 180 different nationalities, Amsterdam is home to one of the widest varieties of nationalities of any city in the world.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The proportion of the population of immigrant origin in the city proper is about 50% and 88% of the population are Dutch citizens.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The first mass immigration in the 20th century was by people from Indonesia, who came to Amsterdam after the independence of the Dutch East Indies in the 1940s and 1950s.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] In the 1960s guest workers from Turkey, Morocco, Italy, and Spain immigrated to Amsterdam.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] After the independence of Suriname in 1975, a large wave of Surinamese settled in Amsterdam, mostly in the Bijlmer area.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Other immigrants, including refugees asylum seekers and undocumented immigrants, came from Europe, the Americas, Asia, and Africa.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] In the 1970s and 1980s, many 'old' Amsterdammers moved to 'new' cities like Almere and Purmerend, prompted by the third Land-use planning bill of the Dutch Government.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] This bill promoted suburbanization and arranged for new developments in so-called "groeikernen", literally *cores of growth*.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Young professionals and artists moved into neighborhoods De Pijp and the Jordaan abandoned by these Amsterdammers.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The non-Western immigrants settled mostly in the social housing projects in Amsterdam-West and the Bijlmer.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] In 2006, people of non-Western origin made up approximately one-fifth of the population of Amsterdam, and more than 30% of the city's children.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] A slight majority of the residents of Amsterdam have at least one parent who was born outside the country.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] However, a much larger majority has at least one parent who was born inside the country (intercultural marriages are common in the city).
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Only a third of inhabitants under 15 are *autochthons (*person with two parents of Dutch origin).
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] In 2023, *autochthons* were a minority in 40% of Amsterdam's neighborhoods.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Segregation along ethnic lines is visible, with people of non-Western origin, considered a separate group by Statistics Netherlands, concentrating in specific neighborhoods especially in Nieuw-West, Zeeburg, Bijlmer and in certain areas of Amsterdam-Noord.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] In 2000, Christians formed the largest religious group in the city (28% of the population).
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The next largest religion was Islam (8%), most of whose followers were Sunni.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] By 2015, this remained largely unchanged, with a slight decrease in the Muslim population to 7.1%.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam has been one of the municipalities in the Netherlands that provided immigrants with extensive and free Dutch-language courses, which have benefited many immigrants.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] In 1578, the largely Catholic city of Amsterdam joined the revolt against Spanish rule, late in comparison to other major northern Dutch cities.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Catholic priests were driven out of the city.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Following the Dutch takeover, all churches were converted to Protestant worship.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Calvinism was declared the main religion.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] It was forbidden to openly profess Roman Catholicism and the Catholic hierarchy was prohibited until the mid-19th century.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] This led to the establishment of clandestine churches, covert religious buildings hidden in pre-existing buildings.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Catholics, some Jews, and dissenting Protestants worshipped in such buildings.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] A large influx of foreigners of many religions came to 17th-century Amsterdam, in particular Sephardic Jews from Spain and Portugal, Huguenots from France, Lutherans, Mennonites, as well as Protestants from across the Netherlands.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] This led to the establishment of many non-Dutch-speaking churches.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] In 1603, the Jewish received permission to practice their religion in the city.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] In 1639, the first synagogue was consecrated.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The Jews came to call the town "Jerusalem of the West".
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] As they became established in the city, other Christian denominations used converted Catholic chapels to conduct their own services.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The oldest English-language church congregation in the world outside the United Kingdom is found at the Begijnhof.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Regular services there are still offered in English under the auspices of the Church of Scotland.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Being Calvinists, the Huguenots soon integrated into the Dutch Reformed Church, though often retaining their own congregations.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Some, commonly referred to by the moniker 'Walloon', are recognizable today as they offer occasional services in French.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] In the second half of the 17th century, Amsterdam experienced an influx of Ashkenazim, Jews from Central and Eastern Europe.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Jews often fled the pogroms in those areas.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The first Ashkenazis who arrived in Amsterdam were refugees from the Khmelnytsky uprising occurring in Ukraine and the Thirty Years' War, which devastated much of Central Europe.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] They not only founded their own synagogues but had a strong influence on the 'Amsterdam dialect' adding a large Yiddish local vocabulary.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Despite an absence of an official Jewish ghetto, most Jews preferred to live in the eastern part, which used to be the centre of medieval Amsterdam.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The main street of this Jewish neighbourhood was Jodenbreestraat.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The neighbourhood comprised the Waterlooplein and the Nieuwmarkt.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Buildings in this neighbourhood fell into disrepair after the Second World War a large section of the neighbourhood was demolished during the construction of the metro system.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] This led to riots, and as a result, the original plans for large-scale reconstruction were abandoned by the government.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The neighbourhood was rebuilt with smaller-scale residence buildings based on its original layout.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Catholic churches in Amsterdam have been constructed since the restoration of the episcopal hierarchy in 1853.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] One of the principal architects behind the city's Catholic churches, Cuypers, was also responsible for the Amsterdam Centraal station and the Rijksmuseum.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] In 1924, the Catholic Church hosted the International Eucharistic Congress in Amsterdam; numerous Catholic prelates visited the city, where festivities were held in churches and stadiums.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Catholic processions on the public streets, however, were still forbidden under law at the time.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Only in the 20th century was Amsterdam's relation to Catholicism normalised, but despite its far larger population size, the episcopal see of the city was placed in the provincial town of Haarlem.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Historically, Amsterdam has been predominantly Christian.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] In 1900 about 70% of the city's population was Christian; the largest religious denomination was the Dutch Reformed Church, adhered to by about 45% of residents, while members of the Catholic Church formed 25%.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] In recent times, the city's religious demography has diversified due to immigration from former colonies.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Hinduism has been introduced by immigrants from Suriname and several distinct branches of Islam have been brought from various parts of the world.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Islam is now the largest non-Christian religion in Amsterdam.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The large community of Ghanaian immigrants has established African churches, often in parking garages in the Bijlmer area.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam fans out south from the Amsterdam Centraal station and Damrak, the main street off the station.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The oldest area of the town is known as De Wallen (English: "The Quays").
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] It lies to the east of Damrak and contains the city's famous red-light district.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] To the south of De Wallen is the old Jewish quarter of Waterlooplein.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The medieval and colonial age canals of Amsterdam, known as *grachten*, embraces the heart of the city where homes have interesting gables.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Beyond the Grachtengordel are the former working-class areas of Jordaan and de Pijp.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The Museumplein with the city's major museums, the Vondelpark, a 19th-century park named after the Dutch writer Joost van den Vondel, as well as the Plantage neighbourhood, with the zoo, are also located outside the Grachtengordel.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Several parts of the city and the surrounding urban area are polders.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] This can be recognised by the suffix *-meer* which means *lake*, as in Aalsmeer, Bijlmermeer, Haarlemmermeer and Watergraafsmeer.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The Amsterdam canal system is the result of conscious city planning.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] In the early 17th century, when immigration was at a peak, a comprehensive plan was developed that was based on four concentric half-circles of canals with their ends emerging at the IJ bay.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The fourth and outermost canal is the Singelgracht, which is often not mentioned on maps because it is a collective name for all canals in the outer ring.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The Singelgracht should not be confused with the oldest and innermost canal, the Singel.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The canals served for defense, water management and transport.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The defenses took the form of a moat and earthen dikes, with gates at transit points, but otherwise no masonry superstructures.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The original plans have been lost, so historians, such as Ed Taverne, need to speculate on the original intentions: it is thought that the considerations of the layout were purely practical and defensive rather than ornamental.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Construction started in 1613 and proceeded from west to east, across the breadth of the layout, like a gigantic windshield wiper as the historian Geert Mak calls it – and not from the centre outwards, as a popular myth has it.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The canal construction in the southern sector was completed by 1656.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Subsequently, the construction of residential buildings proceeded slowly.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The eastern part of the concentric canal plan, covering the area between the Amstel River and the IJ Bay, has never been implemented.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] In the following centuries, the land was used for parks, senior citizens' homes, theatres, other public facilities, and waterways without much planning.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Over the years, several canals have been filled in, becoming streets or squares, such as the Nieuwezijds Voorburgwal and the Spui.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] After the development of Amsterdam's canals in the 17th century, the city did not grow beyond its borders for two centuries.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] During the 19th century, Samuel Sarphati devised a plan based on the grandeur of Paris and London at that time.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The plan envisaged the construction of new houses, public buildings, and streets just outside the Grachtengordel.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The main aim of the plan, however, was to improve public health.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Although the plan did not expand the city, it did produce some of the largest public buildings to date, like the *Paleis voor Volksvlijt*.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Following Sarphati, civil engineers Jacobus van Niftrik and Jan Kalff designed an entire ring of 19th-century neighbourhoods surrounding the city's centre, with the city preserving the ownership of all land outside the 17th-century limit, thus firmly controlling development.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Most of these neighbourhoods became home to the working class.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] In response to overcrowding, two plans were designed at the beginning of the 20th century which were very different from anything Amsterdam had ever seen before: *Plan Zuid* (designed by the architect Berlage) and *West*.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] These plans involved the development of new neighbourhoods consisting of housing blocks for all social classes.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] After the Second World War, large new neighbourhoods were built in the western, southeastern, and northern parts of the city.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] These new neighbourhoods were built to relieve the city's shortage of living space and give people affordable houses with modern conveniences.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The neighbourhoods consisted mainly of large housing blocks located among green spaces, connected to wide roads, making the neighbourhoods accessible by motor car.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The western suburbs which were built in that period are collectively called the Westelijke Tuinsteden.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The area to the southeast of the city built during the same period is known as the Bijlmer.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam has a rich architectural history.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The oldest building in Amsterdam is the Oude Kerk (English: Old Church), at the heart of the Wallen, consecrated in 1306.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The oldest wooden building is *Het Houten Huys* at the Begijnhof.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] It was constructed around 1425 and is one of only two existing wooden buildings.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] It is also one of the few examples of Gothic architecture in Amsterdam.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The oldest stone building in the Netherlands, The Moriaan is built in 's-Hertogenbosch.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] In the 16th century, wooden buildings were razed and replaced with brick ones.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] During this period, many buildings were constructed in the architectural style of the Renaissance.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Buildings of this period are very recognisable with their stepped gable façades, which is the common Dutch Renaissance style.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam quickly developed its own Renaissance architecture.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] These buildings were built according to the principles of the architect Hendrick de Keyser.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] One of the most striking buildings designed by Hendrick de Keyser is the Westerkerk.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] In the 17th century baroque architecture became very popular, as it was elsewhere in Europe.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] This roughly coincided with Amsterdam's Golden Age.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The leading architects of this style in Amsterdam were Jacob van Campen, Philips Vingboons and Daniel Stalpaert.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Philip Vingboons designed splendid merchants' houses throughout the city.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] A famous building in baroque style in Amsterdam is the Royal Palace on Dam Square.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Throughout the 18th century, Amsterdam was heavily influenced by French culture.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] This is reflected in the architecture of that period.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Around 1815, architects broke with the baroque style and started building in different neo-styles.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Most Gothic style buildings date from that era and are therefore said to be built in a neo-gothic style.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] At the end of the 19th century, the Jugendstil or Art Nouveau style became popular and many new buildings were constructed in this architectural style.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Since Amsterdam expanded rapidly during this period, new buildings adjacent to the city centre were also built in this style.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The houses in the vicinity of the Museum Square in Amsterdam Oud-Zuid are an example of Jugendstil.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The last style that was popular in Amsterdam before the modern era was Art Deco.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam had its own version of the style, which was called the Amsterdamse School.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Whole districts were built in this style, such as the *Rivierenbuurt*.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] A notable feature of the façades of buildings designed in Amsterdamse School is that they are highly decorated and ornate, with oddly shaped windows and doors.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The old city centre is the focal point of all the architectural styles before the end of the 19th century.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Jugendstil and Georgian are mostly found outside the city centre in the neighbourhoods built in the early 20th century, although there are also some striking examples of these styles in the city centre.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Most historic buildings in the city centre and nearby are houses, such as the famous merchants' houses lining the canals.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam has many parks, open spaces, and squares throughout the city.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The Vondelpark, the largest park in the city, is located in the Oud-Zuid neighbourhood and is named after the 17th-century Amsterdam author Joost van den Vondel.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Yearly, the park has around 10 million visitors.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] In the park is an open-air theatre, a playground, and several horeca facilities.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] In the Zuid borough, is the Beatrixpark, named after Queen Beatrix.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Between Amsterdam and Amstelveen is the Amsterdamse Bos ("Amsterdam Forest"), the largest recreational area in Amsterdam.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Annually, almost 4.5 million people visit the park, which has a size of 1,000 hectares (2,500 acres) and is approximately three times the size of Central Park.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The Amstelpark in the Zuid borough houses the Rieker windmill, which dates to 1636.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Other parks include the Sarphatipark in the De Pijp neighbourhood, the Oosterpark in the Oost borough and the Westerpark in the Westerpark neighbourhood.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The city has three beaches: Nemo Beach, Citybeach "Het stenen hoofd" (Silodam), and Blijburg, all located in the Centrum borough.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The city has many open squares (*plein* in Dutch).
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] The namesake of the city as the site of the original dam, Dam Square, is the main city square and has the Royal Palace and National Monument.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Museumplein hosts various museums, including the Rijksmuseum, Van Gogh Museum, and Stedelijk Museum.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p01] Other squares include Rembrandtplein, Muntplein, Nieuwmarkt, Leidseplein, Spui and Waterlooplein.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam is the financial and business capital of the Netherlands.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] A substantial number of large corporations and banks' headquarters are located in the Amsterdam area, including: AkzoNobel, Heineken International, ING Group, ABN AMRO, TomTom, Delta Lloyd Group, Booking.com and Philips.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Although many small offices remain along the historic canals, centrally based companies have increasingly relocated outside Amsterdam's city centre.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The adjoining municipality of Amstelveen is the location of KPMG International's global headquarters.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Other non-Dutch companies have chosen to settle in communities surrounding Amsterdam since they allow freehold property ownership, whereas Amsterdam retains ground rent.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The Amsterdam Stock Exchange (AEX), now part of Euronext, is the world's oldest stock exchange and, due to Brexit, has overtaken LSE as the largest bourse in Europe.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] It is near Dam Square in the city centre.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The Port of Amsterdam is the fourth-largest port in Europe, the 38th largest port in the world, and the second-largest port in the Netherlands by metric tons of cargo.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] In 2014, the Port of Amsterdam had a cargo throughput of 97,4 million tons of cargo, which was mostly bulk cargo.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam has the biggest cruise port in the Netherlands with more than 150 cruise ships every year.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] In 2019, the new lock in IJmuiden opened; since then, the port has been able to grow to 125 million tonnes in capacity.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam is one of the most popular tourist destinations in Europe, receiving more than 5.34 million international visitors annually; this is excluding the 16 million day-trippers visiting the city every year.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The number of visitors has been growing steadily over the past decade.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] This can be attributed to an increasing number of European visitors.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Two-thirds of the hotels are located in the city's centre.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Hotels with four or five stars contribute 42% of the total beds available and 41% of the overnight stays in Amsterdam.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The room occupation rate was 85% in 2017, up from 78% in 2006.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The majority of tourists (74%) originate from Europe.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The largest group of non-European visitors come from the United States, accounting for 14% of the total.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Certain years have a theme in Amsterdam to attract extra tourists.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] For example, the year 2006 was designated "Rembrandt 400", to celebrate the 400th birthday of Rembrandt van Rijn.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Some hotels offer special arrangements or activities during these years.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The average number of guests per year staying at the four campsites around the city ranges from 12,000 to 65,000.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] In 2023, the city began running a campaign to dissuade British men between the ages of 18 and 35 from coming to the city as tourists.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The ad shows young men being handcuffed by police and is part of a new campaign to clean up the city's reputation.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] On 25 May 2023, in a bid to crackdown on wild tourist behaviour, the city banned weed smoking in public areas in and around the red light district.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] De Wallen, also known as Walletjes or Rosse Buurt, is a designated area for legalised prostitution and is Amsterdam's largest and best-known red-light district.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] This neighbourhood has become a famous attraction for tourists.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] It consists of a network of canals, streets, and alleys containing several hundred small, one-room apartments rented by sex workers who offer their services from behind a window or glass door, typically illuminated with red lights.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] In recent years, the city government has been closing and repurposing the famous red-light district windows to clean up the area and reduce the amount of party and sex tourism.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Shops in Amsterdam range from large high-end department stores such as De Bijenkorf founded in 1870 to small specialty shops.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam's high-end shops are found in the streets P.C.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Hooftstraat and *Cornelis Schuytstraat*, which are located in the vicinity of the Vondelpark.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] One of Amsterdam's busiest high streets is the narrow, medieval Kalverstraat in the heart of the city.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Other shopping areas include the *Negen Straatjes* and Haarlemmerdijk and Haarlemmerstraat.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] *Negen Straatjes* are nine narrow streets within the *Grachtengordel*, the concentric canal system of Amsterdam.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The Negen Straatjes differ from other shopping districts with the presence of a large diversity of privately owned shops.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The Haarlemmerstraat and Haarlemmerdijk were voted the best shopping street in the Netherlands in 2011.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] These streets have as the *Negen Straatjes* a large diversity of privately owned shops.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The city also features a large number of open-air markets such as the Albert Cuyp Market, Westerstraat-markt, Ten Katemarkt, and Dappermarkt.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Some of these markets are held daily, like the Albert Cuypmarkt and the Dappermarkt.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Others, like the Westerstraatmarkt, are held every week.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Several fashion brands and designers are based in Amsterdam.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Fashion designers include Iris van Herpen, Mart Visser, Viktor & Rolf, Marlies Dekkers and Frans Molenaar.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Fashion models like Yfke Sturm, Doutzen Kroes and Kim Noorda started their careers in Amsterdam.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam has its garment centre in the World Fashion Center.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Fashion photographers Inez van Lamsweerde and Vinoodh Matadin were born in Amsterdam.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] During the later part of the 16th century, Amsterdam's Rederijkerskamer (Chamber of rhetoric) organised contests between different Chambers in the reading of poetry and drama.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] In 1637, Schouwburg, the first theatre in Amsterdam was built, opening on 3 January 1638.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The first ballet performances in the Netherlands were given in Schouwburg in 1642 with the *Ballet of the Five Senses*.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] In the 18th century, French theatre became popular.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] While Amsterdam was under the influence of German music in the 19th century there were few national opera productions; the Hollandse Opera of Amsterdam was built in 1888 for the specific purpose of promoting Dutch opera.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] In the 19th century, popular culture was centred on the Nes area in Amsterdam (mainly vaudeville and music-hall).
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] An improved metronome was invented in 1812 by Dietrich Nikolaus Winkel.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The Rijksmuseum (1885) and Stedelijk Museum (1895) were built and opened.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] In 1888, the Concertgebouworkest orchestra was established.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] With the 20th century came cinema, radio and television.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Though most studios are located in Hilversum and Aalsmeer, Amsterdam's influence on programming is very strong.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Many people who work in the television industry live in Amsterdam.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Also, the headquarters of the Dutch SBS Broadcasting Group is located in Amsterdam.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] There are also a number of cultural centers based in the city that produce public programs about the arts, sciences, politics and history, including de Balie and the John Adams Institute.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The most important museums of Amsterdam are located on the Museumplein (Museum Square), located at the southwestern side of the Rijksmuseum.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] It was created in the last quarter of the 19th century on the grounds of the former World's fair.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The northeastern part of the square is bordered by the large Rijksmuseum.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] In front of the Rijksmuseum on the square itself is a long, rectangular pond.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] This is transformed into an ice rink in winter.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The northwestern part of the square is bordered by the Van Gogh Museum, House of Bols Cocktail & Genever Experience and Coster Diamonds.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The southwestern border of the Museum Square is the Van Baerlestraat, which is a major thoroughfare in this part of Amsterdam.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The Concertgebouw is located across this street from the square.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] To the southeast of the square are several large houses, one of which contains the American consulate.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] A parking garage can be found underneath the square, as well as a supermarket.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The Museumplein is covered almost entirely with a lawn, except for the northeastern part of the square which is covered with gravel.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The current appearance of the square was realised in 1999 when the square was remodelled.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The square itself is the most prominent site in Amsterdam for festivals and outdoor concerts, especially in the summer.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Plans were made in 2008 to remodel the square again because many inhabitants of Amsterdam are not happy with its current appearance.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The Rijksmuseum possesses the largest and most important collection of classical Dutch art.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Its collection consists of nearly one million objects.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The artist most associated with Amsterdam is Rembrandt, whose work, and the work of his pupils, is displayed in the Rijksmuseum.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Rembrandt's masterpiece *The Night Watch* is one of the top pieces of art in the museum.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] It also houses paintings from artists like Bartholomeus van der Helst, Johannes Vermeer, Frans Hals, Ferdinand Bol, Albert Cuyp, Jacob van Ruisdael and Paulus Potter.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Aside from paintings, the collection consists of a large variety of decorative art.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] This ranges from Delftware to giant doll-houses from the 17th century.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The architect of the gothic revival building was P.J.H.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The museum underwent a 10-year, 375 million euro renovation starting in 2003.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The full collection was reopened to the public on 13 April 2013.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The Rijksmuseum has remained the most visited museum in Amsterdam with 2.4 million visitors in 2024.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Van Gogh lived in Amsterdam for a short while and there is a museum dedicated to his work.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The museum is housed in one of the few modern buildings in this area of Amsterdam.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The building was designed by Gerrit Rietveld.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] This building is where the permanent collection is displayed.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] A new building was added to the museum in 1999.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] This building, known as the performance wing, was designed by Japanese architect Kisho Kurokawa.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Its purpose is to house temporary exhibitions of the museum.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Some of Van Gogh's most famous paintings, like *The Potato Eaters* and *Sunflowers*, are in the collection.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The Van Gogh museum is the second most visited museum in Amsterdam, not far behind the Rijksmuseum in terms of the number of visits, being approximately 1.8 million in 2024.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Next to the Van Gogh Museum stands the Stedelijk Museum.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] This is Amsterdam's most important museum of modern art.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The museum is as old as the square it borders and was opened in 1895.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The permanent collection consists of works of art from artists like Piet Mondrian, Karel Appel, and Kazimir Malevich.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] After renovations lasting several years, the museum opened in September 2012 with a new composite extension that has been called 'The Bathtub' due to its resemblance to one.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam contains many other museums throughout the city.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The modern-styled Nemo is dedicated to child-friendly science exhibitions.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam's musical culture includes a large collection of songs that treat the city nostalgically and lovingly.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The 1949 song "Aan de Amsterdamse grachten" ("On the canals of Amsterdam") was performed and recorded by many artists, including John Kraaijkamp Sr.; the best-known version is probably that by Wim Sonneveld (1962).
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] In the 1950s Johnny Jordaan rose to fame with "Geef mij maar Amsterdam" ("I prefer Amsterdam"), which praises the city above all others (explicitly Paris); Jordaan sang especially about his own neighbourhood, the Jordaan ("Bij ons in de Jordaan").
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Colleagues and contemporaries of Johnny include Tante Leen and Manke Nelis.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Another notable Amsterdam song is "Amsterdam" by Jacques Brel (1964).
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] A 2011 poll by Amsterdam newspaper *Het Parool* that Trio Bier's "Oude Wolf" was voted "Amsterdams lijflied".
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Notable Amsterdam bands from the modern era include the Osdorp Posse and the Ex.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] AFAS Live (formerly known as the Heineken Music Hall) is a concert hall located near the Johan Cruyff Arena (known as the Amsterdam Arena until 2018).
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Its main purpose is to serve as a podium for pop concerts for big audiences.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Many famous international artists have performed there.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Two other notable venues, Paradiso and the Melkweg are located near the Leidseplein.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Both focus on broad programming, ranging from indie rock to hip-hop, R&B, and other popular genres.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Other subcultural music venues are OCCII, OT301, De Nieuwe Anita, Winston Kingdom, and Zaal 100.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Jazz has a strong following in Amsterdam, with the Bimhuis being the premier venue.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] In 2012, Ziggo Dome was opened, also near Amsterdam Arena, a state-of-the-art indoor music arena.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] AFAS Live is also host to many electronic dance music festivals, alongside many other venues.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Armin van Buuren and Tiesto, some of the world's leading Trance DJs hail from the Netherlands and frequently perform in Amsterdam.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Each year in October, the city hosts the Amsterdam Dance Event (ADE) which is one of the leading electronic music conferences and one of the biggest club festivals for electronic music in the world, attracting over 350,000 visitors each year.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Another popular dance festival is 5daysoff, which takes place in the venues Paradiso and Melkweg.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] In the summertime, there are several big outdoor dance parties in or nearby Amsterdam, such as Awakenings, Dance Valley, Mystery Land, Loveland, A Day at the Park, Welcome to the Future, and Valtifest.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam has a world-class symphony orchestra, the Royal Concertgebouw Orchestra.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Their home is the Concertgebouw, which is across the Van Baerlestraat from the Museum Square.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] It is considered by critics to be a concert hall with some of the best acoustics in the world.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The building contains three halls, Grote Zaal, Kleine Zaal, and Spiegelzaal.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Some nine hundred concerts and other events per year take place in the Concertgebouw, for a public of over 700,000, making it one of the most-visited concert halls in the world.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The opera house of Amsterdam is located adjacent to the city hall.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Therefore, the two buildings combined are often called the Stopera, (a word originally coined by protesters against its very construction: *Stop the Opera[-house]*).
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] This huge modern complex, opened in 1986, lies in the former Jewish neighbourhood at *Waterlooplein* next to the river Amstel.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The *Stopera* is the home base of Dutch National Opera, Dutch National Ballet and the Holland Symfonia.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Muziekgebouw aan 't IJ is a concert hall, which is located in the IJ near the central station.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Its concerts perform mostly modern classical music.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Located adjacent to it, is the *Bimhuis*, a concert hall for improvised and jazz music.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam has three main theatre buildings.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The Stadsschouwburg at the Leidseplein is the home base of Toneelgroep Amsterdam.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Most plays are performed in the Grote Zaal (Great Hall).
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The normal program of events encompasses all sorts of theatrical forms.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] In 2009, the new hall of the Stadsschouwburg Amsterdam, Toneelgroep Amsterdam, and Melkweg opened, and the renovation of the front end of the theatre was ready.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The Dutch National Opera and Ballet (formerly known as *Het Muziektheater*), dating from 1986, is the principal opera house and home to Dutch National Opera and Dutch National Ballet.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Royal Theatre Carré was built as a permanent circus theatre in 1887 and is currently mainly used for musicals, cabaret performances, and pop concerts.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The recently re-opened DeLaMar Theater houses more commercial plays and musicals.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] A new theatre has also moved into the Amsterdam scene in 2014, joining other established venues: Theater Amsterdam is located in the west part of Amsterdam, on the Danzigerkade.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] It is housed in a modern building with a panoramic view over the harbour.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The theatre is the first-ever purpose-built venue to showcase a single play entitled ANNE, the play based on Anne Frank's life.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] On the east side of town, there is a small theatre in a converted bathhouse, the Badhuistheater.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The theatre often has English programming.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The Netherlands has a tradition of cabaret or *kleinkunst*, which combines music, storytelling, commentary, theatre, and comedy.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Cabaret dates back to the 1930s and artists like Wim Kan, Wim Sonneveld, and Toon Hermans were pioneers of this form of art in the Netherlands.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] In Amsterdam are the Kleinkunstacademie (English: Cabaret Academy) and Nederlied Kleinkunstkoor (English: Cabaret Choir).
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Contemporary popular artists are Youp van 't Hek, Freek de Jonge, Herman Finkers, Hans Teeuwen, Theo Maassen, Herman van Veen, Najib Amhali, Raoul Heertje, Jörgen Raymann, Brigitte Kaandorp and Comedytrain.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The English-spoken comedy scene was established with the founding of Boom Chicago in 1993.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] They have their own theatre at Leidseplein.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam is famous for its vibrant and diverse nightlife.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] They range from large and modern to small and cosy.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The typical *Bruine Kroeg* (brown *café*) breathes a more old-fashioned atmosphere with dimmed lights, candles, and somewhat older clientele.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] These brown cafés mostly offer a wide range of local and international artisanal beers.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Most *cafés* have terraces in summertime.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] A common sight on the Leidseplein during summer is a square full of terraces packed with people drinking beer or wine.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Many restaurants can be found in Amsterdam as well.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Since Amsterdam is a multicultural city, a lot of different ethnic restaurants can be found.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Restaurants range from being rather luxurious and expensive to being ordinary and affordable.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam also possesses many discothèques.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The two main nightlife areas for tourists are the Leidseplein and the Rembrandtplein.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The Paradiso, Melkweg and Sugar Factory are cultural centres, which turn into discothèques on some nights.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] In 2008, there were 140 festivals and events in Amsterdam.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] During the same year, Amsterdam was designated as the World Book Capital for one year by UNESCO.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] On Koningsdag—which is held each year on 27 April—hundreds of thousands of people travel to Amsterdam to celebrate with the city's residents.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The entire city becomes overcrowded with people buying products from the *free market*, or visiting one of the many music concerts.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The yearly Holland Festival attracts international artists and visitors from all over Europe.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam Gay Pride is a yearly local LGBT parade of boats in Amsterdam's canals, held on the first Saturday in August.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The annual Uitmarkt is a three-day cultural event at the start of the cultural season in late August.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] It offers previews of many different artists, such as musicians and poets, who perform on podia.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam is home of the *Eredivisie* football club AFC Ajax.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The stadium Johan Cruyff Arena is the home of Ajax.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] It is located in the south-east of the city next to the new Amsterdam Bijlmer ArenA railway station.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Before moving to their current location in 1996, Ajax played their regular matches in the now demolished De Meer Stadion in the eastern part of the city or in the Olympic Stadium.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] In 1928, Amsterdam hosted the Summer Olympics.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The Olympic Stadium built for the occasion has been completely restored and is now used for cultural and sporting events, such as the Amsterdam Marathon.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] In 1920, Amsterdam assisted in hosting some of the sailing events for the Summer Olympics held in neighbouring Antwerp, Belgium by hosting events at Buiten IJ.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] They had also made a bid to host the 1952 and 1992 Summer Olympics but lost to Helsinki and Barcelona.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The city holds the Dam to Dam Run, a 16 km (10 mi) race from Amsterdam to Zaandam, as well as the Amsterdam Marathon.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The ice hockey team Amstel Tijgers plays in the Jaap Eden ice rink.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The team competes in the Dutch Ice Hockey Premier League.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Speed skating championships have been held on the 400-meter lane of this ice rink.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam holds two American football franchises: the Amsterdam Crusaders and the Amsterdam Panthers.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The Amsterdam Pirates baseball team competes in the Dutch Major League.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] There are three field hockey teams: Amsterdam, Pinoké, and Hurley, who play their matches around the Wagener Stadium in the nearby city of Amstelveen.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The basketball team MyGuide Amsterdam competes in the Dutch premier division and play their games in the Sporthallen Zuid.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] There is one rugby club in Amsterdam, which also hosts sports training classes such as RTC (Rugby Talenten Centrum or Rugby Talent Centre) and the National Rugby Stadium.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Since 1999, the city of Amsterdam honours the best sportsmen and women at the Amsterdam Sports Awards.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Boxer Raymond Joval and field hockey midfielder Carole Thate were the first to receive the awards, in 1999.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam hosted the World Gymnaestrada in 1991 and will do so again in 2023.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The city of Amsterdam is a municipality under the Dutch Municipalities Act.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] It is governed by a directly elected municipal council, a municipal executive, and a mayor.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Since 1981, the municipality of Amsterdam has gradually been divided into semi-autonomous boroughs, called *stadsdelen* or 'districts'.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Over time, a total of 15 boroughs were created.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] As with all Dutch municipalities, Amsterdam is governed by a directly elected municipal council, a municipal executive and a government appointed mayor (*burgemeester*).
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The mayor is a member of the municipal executive board but also has individual responsibilities in maintaining public order.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] She replaces Eberhard van der Laan (Labour Party) who was the Mayor of Amsterdam from 2010 until his death in October 2017.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] After the 2014 municipal council elections, a governing majority of D66, VVD and SP was formed – the first coalition without the Labour Party since World War II.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Next to the mayor, the municipal executive consists of eight *wethouders* ('alderpersons') appointed by the municipal council: four D66 alderpersons, two VVD alderpersons and two SP alderpersons.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] On 18 September 2017, it was announced by Eberhard van der Laan in an open letter to Amsterdam citizens that Kajsa Ollongren would take up his office as acting Mayor of Amsterdam with immediate effect due to ill health.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Ollongren was succeeded as acting Mayor by Eric van der Burg on 26 October 2017 and by Jozias van Aartsen on 4 December 2017.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Unlike most other Dutch municipalities, Amsterdam is subdivided into seven boroughs, called *stadsdelen* or 'districts', and the urban area of Weesp.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] This system was gradually implemented in the 1980s to improve local governance.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The boroughs are responsible for many activities that had previously been run by the central city.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] In 2010, the number of Amsterdam boroughs reached fifteen.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Fourteen of those had their own district council (*deelraad*), elected by a popular vote.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The fifteenth, Westpoort, covers the harbour of Amsterdam and has very few residents.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Therefore, it was governed by the central municipal council.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Under the borough system, municipal decisions are made at the borough level, except for those affairs on the whole city such as major infrastructure projects, which are the jurisdiction of the central municipal authorities.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] In 2010, the borough system was restructured, in which many smaller boroughs merged into larger boroughs.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] In 2014, under a reform of the Dutch Municipalities Act, the Amsterdam boroughs lost much of their autonomous status, as their district councils were abolished.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The municipal council of Amsterdam voted to maintain the borough system by replacing the district councils with smaller, but still directly elected district committees (*bestuurscommissies*).
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Under a municipal ordinance, the new district committees were granted responsibilities through the delegation of regulatory and executive powers by the central municipal council.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] "Amsterdam" is usually understood to refer to the municipality of Amsterdam.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Colloquially, some areas within the municipality, such as the town of Durgerdam, may not be considered part of Amsterdam.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The Amsterdam Department for Research and Statistics uses a fourth conurbation, namely the *Stadsregio Amsterdam* ('City Region of Amsterdam').
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The city region is similar to Greater Amsterdam but includes the municipalities of Zaanstad and Wormerland.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The smallest of these areas is the municipality of Amsterdam with a population of about 870,000 in 2021.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The larger conurbation had a population of over one million.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] It includes the municipalities of Zaanstad, Wormerland, Oostzaan, Diemen, and Amstelveen only, as well as the municipality of Amsterdam.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Greater Amsterdam includes 15 municipalities and had a population of 1,400,000 in 2021.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Though much larger in area, the population of this area is only slightly larger, because the definition excludes the relatively populous municipality of Zaanstad.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The largest area by population, the Metropolitan Region Amsterdam (Dutch: Metropoolregio Amsterdam), has a population of 2,33 million.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] It includes for instance Zaanstad, Wormerland, Muiden, Abcoude, Haarlem, Almere and Lelystad but excludes Graft-De Rijp.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam is part of the conglomerate metropolitan area Randstad, with a total population of 6,659,300 inhabitants.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Of these various metropolitan area configurations, only the *Stadsregio Amsterdam* (City Region of Amsterdam) has a formal governmental status.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Its responsibilities include regional spatial planning and metropolitan public transport concessions.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Under the Dutch Constitution, Amsterdam is the capital of the Netherlands.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Since the 1983 constitutional revision, the constitution mentions "Amsterdam" and "capital" in chapter 2, article 32: The king's confirmation by oath and his coronation take place in "the capital Amsterdam" ("*de hoofdstad Amsterdam*").
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Previous versions of the constitution only mentioned "the city of Amsterdam" ("*de stad Amsterdam*").
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] For a royal investiture, therefore, the States General of the Netherlands (the Dutch Parliament) meets for a ceremonial joint session in Amsterdam.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The ceremony traditionally takes place at the Nieuwe Kerk on Dam Square, immediately after the former monarch has signed the act of abdication at the nearby Royal Palace of Amsterdam.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Normally, however, the Parliament sits in The Hague, the city which has historically been the seat of the Dutch government, the Dutch monarchy, and the Dutch supreme court.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Foreign embassies are also located in The Hague.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The coat of arms of Amsterdam is composed of several historical elements.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] First and centre are three St Andrew's crosses, aligned in a vertical band on the city's shield (although Amsterdam's patron saint was Saint Nicholas).
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] These St Andrew's crosses can also be found on the city shields of neighbours Amstelveen and Ouder-Amstel.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] This part of the coat of arms is the basis of the flag of Amsterdam, flown by the city government, but also as civil ensign for ships registered in Amsterdam.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Second is the Imperial Crown of Austria.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] In 1489, out of gratitude for services and loans, Maximilian I awarded Amsterdam the right to adorn its coat of arms with the king's crown.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Then, in 1508, this was replaced with Maximilian's imperial crown when he was crowned Holy Roman Emperor.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] In the early years of the 17th century, Maximilian's crown in Amsterdam's coat of arms was again replaced, this time with the crown of Emperor Rudolph II, a crown that became the Imperial Crown of Austria.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The lions date from the late 16th century, when the city and province became part of the Republic of the Seven United Netherlands.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Last came the city's official motto: *Heldhaftig, Vastberaden, Barmhartig* ("Heroic, Determined, Merciful"), bestowed on the city in 1947 by Queen Wilhelmina, in recognition of the city's bravery during the Second World War.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Currently, there are sixteen tram routes and five metro routes.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] All are operated by the municipal public transport operator Gemeentelijk Vervoerbedrijf (GVB), which also runs the city bus network.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Four fare-free GVB ferries carry pedestrians and cyclists across the IJ lake to the borough of Amsterdam-Noord, and two fare-charging ferries run east and west along the harbour.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] There are also privately operated water taxis, a water bus, a boat-sharing operation, electric rental boats, and canal cruises, that transport people along Amsterdam's waterways.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Regional buses, and some suburban buses, are operated by Connexxion and EBS.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] International coach services are provided by FlixBus and BlaBlaCar Bus.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] To facilitate easier transport to the centre of Amsterdam, the city has various P+R Locations where people can park their car at an affordable price and transfer to one of the numerous public transport lines.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam was intended in 1932 to be the hub, a kind of Kilometre Zero, of the highway system of the Netherlands, with freeways numbered One to Eight planned to originate from the city.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The outbreak of the Second World War and shifting priorities led to the current situation, where only roads A1, A2, and A4 originate from Amsterdam according to the original plan.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The A3 to Rotterdam was cancelled in 1970 to conserve the Groene Hart.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Road A8, leading north to Zaandam and the A10 Ringroad were opened between 1968 and 1974.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Besides the A1, A2, A4 and A8, several freeways, such as the A7 and A6, carry traffic mainly bound for Amsterdam.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The A10 ringroad surrounding the city connects Amsterdam with the Dutch national network of freeways.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Interchanges on the A10 allow cars to enter the city by transferring to one of the 18 *city roads*, numbered S101 through to S118.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] These city roads are regional roads without grade separation, and sometimes without a central reservation.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The S100 *Centrumring* is a smaller ring road circumnavigating the city's centre.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] In the city centre, driving a car is discouraged.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Parking fees are expensive, and many streets are closed to cars or are one-way.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The local government sponsors carsharing and carpooling initiatives such as *Autodelen* and *Meerijden.nu*.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The local government has also started removing parking spaces in the city in 2019, with the goal of removing 10,000 spaces (roughly 1,500 per year) by 2025.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam is served by ten stations of the Nederlandse Spoorwegen (Dutch Railways).
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Five are intercity stops: Sloterdijk, Zuid, Amstel, Bijlmer ArenA and Amsterdam Centraal.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The stations for local services are: Lelylaan, RAI, Holendrecht, Muiderpoort and Science Park.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam Centraal is also an international railway station.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] From the station, there are regular services to destinations such as Austria, Belgium, Czech Republic, France, Germany, Switzerland and the United Kingdom.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Among these trains are international trains of the Nederlandse Spoorwegen and Deutsche Bahn to Berlin, Eurostar services to Antwerp, Brussels, Paris and London and ICE services to Cologne and Frankfurt.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam Airport Schiphol is less than 20 minutes by train from Amsterdam Centraal station and is served by domestic and international intercity trains, such as Eurostar and EuroCity.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Schiphol is the largest airport in the Netherlands, the third-largest in Europe, and the 14th-largest in the world in terms of passengers.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] It handles over 68 million passengers per year and is the home base of four airlines, KLM, Transavia, Martinair and Arkefly.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] As of 2014, Schiphol was the fifth busiest airport in the world measured by international passenger numbers.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] This airport is 4 meters below sea level.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Although Schiphol is internationally known as Amsterdam Schiphol Airport it lies in the neighbouring municipality of Haarlemmermeer, southwest of the city.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Rotterdam The Hague Airport, a smaller international airport, is also within an hour's drive of the city.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam is one of the most bicycle-friendly large cities in the world and is a centre of bicycle culture with good facilities for cyclists such as bike paths and bike racks, and several guarded bike storage garages (*fietsenstalling*) which can be used.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] According to the most recent figures published by the Central Bureau of Statistics (CBS), in 2015 the 442,693 households (850,000 residents) in Amsterdam together owned 847,000 bicycles – 1.91 bicycles per household.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Theft is widespread—in 2011, about 83,000 bicycles were stolen in Amsterdam.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Bicycles are used by all socio-economic groups because of their convenience, Amsterdam's small size, the 400 km (249 mi) of bike paths, the flat terrain, and the inconvenience of driving an automobile.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam has two universities: the University of Amsterdam (*Universiteit van Amsterdam*, UvA), and the *Vrije Universiteit Amsterdam* (VU).
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The University of Amsterdam is home to Room for Discussion, an independent interview platform that has welcomed a variety of prominent guests including Christine Lagarde, Mario Draghi, Charles Michel, Rob Bauer, and Sviatlana Tsikhanouskaya.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Other institutions for higher education include an art school – Gerrit Rietveld Academie, a university of applied sciences – the Hogeschool van Amsterdam, and the Amsterdamse Hogeschool voor de Kunsten.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam's International Institute of Social History is one of the world's largest documentary and research institutions concerning social history, and especially the history of the labour movement.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam's Hortus Botanicus, founded in the early 17th century, is one of the oldest botanical gardens in the world, with many old and rare specimens, among them the coffee plant that served as the parent for the entire coffee culture in Central and South America.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] There are over 200 primary schools in Amsterdam.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Some of these primary schools base their teachings on particular pedagogic theories like the various Montessori schools.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The biggest Montessori high school in Amsterdam is the Montessori Lyceum Amsterdam.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Many schools, however, are based on religion.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] This used to be primarily Roman Catholicism and various Protestant denominations, but with the influx of Muslim immigrants, there has been a rise in the number of Islamic schools.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Jewish schools can be found in the southern suburbs of Amsterdam.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam is noted for having five independent grammar schools (Dutch: gymnasia), the Vossius Gymnasium, Barlaeus Gymnasium, St.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Ignatius Gymnasium, Het 4e Gymnasium and the Cygnus Gymnasium where a classical curriculum including Latin and classical Greek is taught.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Though believed until recently by many to be an anachronistic and elitist concept that would soon die out, the gymnasia have recently experienced a revival, leading to the formation of a fourth and fifth grammar school in which the three aforementioned schools participate.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Most secondary schools in Amsterdam offer a variety of different levels of education in the same school.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The city also has various colleges ranging from art and design to politics and economics which are mostly also available for students coming from other countries.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam is a prominent centre for national and international media.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam is home to the second-largest Dutch commercial TV group SBS Broadcasting Group, consisting of TV stations SBS6, Net5, and Veronica.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] However, Amsterdam is not considered 'the media city of the Netherlands'.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The town of Hilversum, 30 km (19 mi) south-east of Amsterdam, has been crowned with this unofficial title.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Hilversum is the principal centre for radio and television broadcasting in the Netherlands.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Radio Netherlands, heard worldwide via shortwave radio since the 1920s, is also based there.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Hilversum is home to an extensive complex of audio and television studios belonging to the national broadcast production company NOS, as well as to the studios and offices of all the Dutch public broadcasting organisations and many commercial TV production companies.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] In 2012, the music video for "Live My Life" by Far East Movement was filmed in various parts of Amsterdam.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Several movies have been filmed in Amsterdam, including the James Bond film *Diamonds Are Forever*, *Ocean's Twelve*, *Girl with a Pearl Earring*, *Kidnapping Mr.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Heineken*, *Layer Cake* and *The Hitman's Bodyguard*.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam is also featured in John Green's book *The Fault in Our Stars*, which was made into a film that also partly takes place in Amsterdam.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] In 2003, the British drama series *Bad Girls* filmed scenes on location in Amsterdam.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] The scenes shows the male officers on a weekend trip in the red light district where they encounter escapee Shell Dockley and return her to the UK.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam appears as a multiplayer map in *Modern Warfare II* under the name Breenbergh Hotel.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam also appears in *Black Ops Cold War* in an update, having players fight through the city.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] From the late 1960s onwards many buildings in Amsterdam have been squatted both for housing and for use as social centres.
[src:beam-engine/amsterdam-p02] A number of these squats have legalised and become well known, such as OCCII, OT301, Paradiso and Vrankrijk.
[src:beam-engine/beam-engine] A **beam engine** is a type of steam engine where a pivoted overhead beam is used to apply the force from a vertical piston to a vertical connecting rod.
[src:beam-engine/beam-engine] This configuration, with the engine directly driving a pump, was first used by Thomas Newcomen around 1705 to remove water from mines in Cornwall.
[src:beam-engine/beam-engine] The efficiency of the engines was improved by engineers including James Watt, who added a separate condenser; Jonathan Hornblower and Arthur Woolf, who compounded the cylinders; and William McNaught, who devised a method of compounding an existing engine.
[src:beam-engine/beam-engine] Beam engines were first used to pump water out of mines or into canals but could be used to pump water to supplement the flow for a waterwheel powering a mill.
[src:beam-engine/beam-engine] The **rotative beam engine** is a later design of beam engine where the connecting rod drives a flywheel by means of a crank (or, historically, by means of a sun and planet gear).
[src:beam-engine/beam-engine] These beam engines could be used to directly power the line-shafting in a mill.
[src:beam-engine/beam-engine] They also could be used to power steam ships.
[src:beam-engine/beam-engine] The first beam engines were water-powered and used to pump water from mines.
[src:beam-engine/beam-engine] A preserved example may be seen at the Straitsteps Lead Mine in Wanlockhead in Scotland.
[src:beam-engine/beam-engine] Beam engines were extensively used to power pumps on the English canal system when it was expanded by means of locks early in the Industrial Revolution, and also to drain water from mines in the same period, and as winding engines.
[src:beam-engine/beam-engine] The first steam-related beam engine was developed by Thomas Newcomen.
[src:beam-engine/beam-engine] This was not, strictly speaking, steam powered, as the steam introduced below the piston was condensed to create a partial vacuum thus allowing atmospheric pressure to push down the piston.
[src:beam-engine/beam-engine] It was therefore called an Atmospheric Engine.
[src:beam-engine/beam-engine] The Newcomen atmospheric engine was adopted by many mines in Cornwall and elsewhere, but it was relatively inefficient and consumed a large quantity of fuel.
[src:beam-engine/beam-engine] The engine was improved by John Smeaton but James Watt resolved the main inefficiencies of the Newcomen engine in his Watt steam engine by the addition of a separate condenser, thus allowing the cylinder to remain hot.
[src:beam-engine/beam-engine] Technically this was still an atmospheric engine until (under subsequent patents) he enclosed the upper part of the cylinder, introducing steam to also push the piston down.
[src:beam-engine/beam-engine] This made it a true steam engine and arguably confirms him as the inventor of the steam engine.
[src:beam-engine/beam-engine] He also patented the centrifugal governor and the parallel motion. the latter allowed the replacement of chains round an arch head and thus allowed its use as a rotative engine.
[src:beam-engine/beam-engine] His patents remained in place until the start of the 19th Century and some say that this held back development.
[src:beam-engine/beam-engine] However, in reality development had been ongoing by others and at the end of the patent period there was an explosion of new ideas and improvements.
[src:beam-engine/beam-engine] Watt's beam engines were used commercially in much larger numbers and many continued to run for 100 years or more.
[src:beam-engine/beam-engine] Watt held patents on key aspects of his engine's design, but his rotative engine was equally restricted by James Pickard's patent of the simple crank.
[src:beam-engine/beam-engine] The beam engine went on to be considerably improved and enlarged in the tin- and copper-rich areas of south west England, which enabled the draining of the deep mines that existed there.
[src:beam-engine/beam-engine] Consequently, the Cornish beam engines became world-famous, as they remain among the most massive beam engines ever constructed.
[src:beam-engine/beam-engine] Because of the number of patents on various parts of the engines and the consequences of patent infringements, examples exist of Beam Engines with no makers name on any of the parts (Hollycombe Steam Collection).
[src:beam-engine/beam-engine] In a rotative beam engine, the piston is mounted vertically, and the piston rod drives the beam as before.
[src:beam-engine/beam-engine] A connecting rod from the other end of the beam, rather than driving a pump rod, now drives a flywheel.
[src:beam-engine/beam-engine] Early Watt engines used Watt's patent sun and planet gear, rather than a simple crank, as use of the latter was protected by a patent owned by James Pickard.
[src:beam-engine/beam-engine] Once the patent had expired, the simple crank was employed universally.
[src:beam-engine/beam-engine] Once rotary motion had been achieved a drive belt could be attached beside the flywheel.
[src:beam-engine/beam-engine] This transmitted the power to other drive shafts and from these other belts could then be attached to power a variety of static machinery e.g. threshing, grinding or milling machines.
[src:beam-engine/beam-engine] The first steam-powered ships used variants of the rotative beam engine.
[src:beam-engine/beam-engine] These marine steam engines – known as side-lever, grasshopper, crosshead, or 'walking beam', among others – all varied from the original land-based machines by locating the beam or beams in different positions to take up less room on board ship.
[src:beam-engine/beam-engine] Compounding involves two or more cylinders; low-pressure steam from the first, high-pressure, cylinder is passed to the second cylinder where it expands further and provides more drive.
[src:beam-engine/beam-engine] This is the compound effect; the waste steam from this can produce further work if it is then passed into a condenser in the normal way.
[src:beam-engine/beam-engine] The first experiment with compounding was conducted by Jonathan Hornblower, who took out a patent in 1781.
[src:beam-engine/beam-engine] His first engine was installed at Tincroft Mine, Cornwall.
[src:beam-engine/beam-engine] It had two cylinders – one 21-inch (0.53 m) diameter with 6-foot (1.8 m) stroke and one 27-inch (0.69 m) diameter with 8-foot (2.4 m) stroke – placed alongside each other at one end of the beam.
[src:beam-engine/beam-engine] The early engines showed little performance gain: the steam pressure was too low, interconnecting pipes were of small diameter and the condenser ineffective.
[src:beam-engine/beam-engine] At this time the laws of thermodynamics were not adequately understood, particularly the concept of absolute zero.
[src:beam-engine/beam-engine] Engineers such as Arthur Woolf were trying to tackle an engineering problem with an imperfect understanding of the physics.
[src:beam-engine/beam-engine] In particular, their valve gear was cutting-in at the wrong position in the stroke, not allowing for expansive working in the cylinder.
[src:beam-engine/beam-engine] Successful Woolf compound engines were produced in 1814, for the Wheal Abraham copper mine and the Wheal Vor tin mine.
[src:beam-engine/beam-engine] William McNaught patented a compound beam engine in 1845.
[src:beam-engine/beam-engine] On a beam engine of the standard Boulton & Watt design he placed a high-pressure cylinder, on the opposite side of the beam to the existing single cylinder, where the water pump was normally fitted.
[src:beam-engine/beam-engine] This had two important effects: it massively reduced the pressure on the beam, and the connecting steam pipe, being long, acted as an expansive receiver – the element missing in the Woolf design.
[src:beam-engine/beam-engine] This modification could be made retrospectively, and engines so modified were said to be "McNaughted".
[src:beam-engine/beam-engine] The advantages of a compound engine were not significant at pressures under 60 pounds per square inch (410 kPa), but showed at over 100 psi (690 kPa).
